t + optional vowel sign or virama)'''\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| '''vowels'''\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:.5em auto\"\n|-\n| ''virama'' || \u1734\n{{Script|Tglg|  \u1714}}\n|-\n| a || {{Script|Tglg| \u1700}}\n|-\n| i<br /> ''e'' || {{Script|Tglg| \u1701}}\n|-\n| u<br /> ''o'' || {{Script|Tglg| \u1702}}\n|}\n| '''k'''\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:.5em auto\"\n|-\n|/k/\n\n<br />\n|{{Script|Tglg|\u1703\u1714}}<br />\n|-\n| ka  || {{Script|Tglg|\u1703}}\n|-\n| ki<br /> ''ke'' || {{Script|Tglg|\u1703\u1712}}\n|-\n| ku\n<br /> ''ko''\n|{{Script|Tglg|\u1703\u1713\u1713}}\n|}\n| '''g'''\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:.5em auto\"\n|-\n|/g/||{{Script|Tglg|\u1704\u1714}}\n|-\n| ga || {{Script|Tglg|\u1704}}\n|-\n| gi<br /> ''ge'' || {{Script|Tglg|\u1704\u1712}}\n|-\n| gu\n<br /> ''go''\n<br />||{{Script|Tglg|\u1704\u1713}}\n|}\n| '''ng'''\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:.5em auto\"\n|-\n|/\u014b/\n|{{Script|Tglg|\u1705\u1714}}\n|-\n| nga || {{Script|Tglg|\u1705}}\n|-\n| ngi<br /> ''nge'' ||{{Script|Tglg|\u1705\u1712}}\n|-\n| ngu<br /> ''ngo'' ||{{Script|Tglg|\u1705\u1713}}\n|}\n| '''t'''\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:.5em auto\"\n|-\n|/t/\n|{{Script|Tglg|\u1706\u1714}}\n|-\n| ta || {{Script|Tglg|\u1706}}\n|-\n| ti<br /> ''te'' || {{Script|Tglg|\u1706\u1712}}\n|-\n| tu<br /> ''to'' || {{Script|Tglg|\u1706\u1713}}\n|}\n| '''d/r'''\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:.5em auto\"\n|-\n| /d/ /r/\n<br />\n|{{Script|Tglg|\u1707\u1714}}\n|-\n| da/ra || {{Script|Tglg|\u1707}}\n|-\n| di/ri<br /> ''de/re'' || {{Script|Tglg|\u1707\u1712}}\n|-\n| du/ru<br /> ''do/ro'' || {{Script|Tglg|\u1707\u1713}}\n|}\n| '''n'''\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:.5em auto\"\n|-\n|/n/\n|{{Script|Tglg|\u1708\u1714}}\n|-\n| na || {{Script|Tglg|\u1708}}\n|-\n| ni<br /> ''ne'' ||{{Script|Tglg|\u1708\u1712}}\n|-\n| nu<br /> ''no'' ||{{Script|Tglg|\u1708\u1713}}\n|}\n| '''p/f'''\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:.5em auto\"\n|-\n|/p/ /f/\n|{{Script|Tglg|\u1709\u1714}}\n|-\n| pa/fa || {{Script|Tglg|\u1709}}\n|-\n| pi/fi<br /> ''pe/fe'' || {{Script|Tglg|\u1709\u1712}}\n|-\n| pu/fu<br /> ''po/fo'' || {{Script|Tglg|\u1709\u1713}}\n|}\n| '''b/v'''\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:.5em auto\"\n|-\n|/b/ /v/\n|{{Script|Tglg|\u170a\u1714}}\n|-\n| ba/va  || {{Script|Tglg|\u170a}}\n|-\n| bi/vi<br /> ''be/vi'' || {{Script|Tglg|\u170a\u1712}}\n|-\n| bu/vu<br /> ''bo/vo'' || {{Script|Tglg|\u170a\u1713}}\n|}\n| '''m'''\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:.5em auto\"\n|-\n|/m/\n|{{Script|Tglg|\u170b\u1714}}\n|-\n| ma || {{Script|Tglg|\u170b}}\n|-\n| mi<br /> ''me'' || {{Script|Tglg|\u170b\u1712}}\n|-\n| mu<br /> ''mo'' || {{Script|Tglg|\u170b\u1713}}\n|}\n| '''y'''\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:.5em auto\"\n|-\n|/y/\n|{{Script|Tglg|\u170c\u1714}}\n|-\n| ya || {{Script|Tglg|\u170c}}\n|-\n| yi<br /> ''ye'' || {{Script|Tglg|\u170c\u1712}}\n|-\n| yu<br /> ''yo'' || {{Script|Tglg|\u170c\u1713}}\n|}\n| '''l'''\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:.5em auto\"\n|-\n|/l/\n|{{Script|Tglg|\u170e\u1714}}\n|-\n| la || {{Script|Tglg|\u170e}}\n|-\n| li<br /> ''le'' || {{Script|Tglg|\u170e\u1712}}\n|-\n| lu<br /> ''lo'' || {{Script|Tglg|\u170e\u1713}}\n|}\n| '''w'''\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:.5em auto\"\n|-\n|/w/\n|{{Script|Tglg|\u170f\u1714}}\n|-\n| wa || {{Script|Tglg|\u170f}}\n|-\n| wi<br /> ''we'' || {{Script|Tglg|\u170f\u1712}}\n|-\n| wu<br /> ''wo'' || {{Script|Tglg|\u170f\u1713}}\n|}\n| '''s/z'''\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:.5em auto\"\n|-\n|/s/ /z/\n|{{Script|Tglg|\u1710\u1714}}\n|-\n| sa/za || {{Script|Tglg|\u1710}}\n|-\n| si/zi<br /> ''se/ze'' || {{Script|Tglg|\u1710\u1712}}\n|-\n| su/zu<br /> ''so/zo'' || {{Script|Tglg|\u1710\u1713}}\n|}\n| '''h'''\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:.5em auto\"\n|-\n|/h/\n|{{Script|Tglg|\u1711\u1714}}\n|-\n| ha || {{Script|Tglg|\u1711}}\n|-\n| hi<br /> ''he'' || {{Script|Tglg|\u1711\u1712}}\n|-\n| hu<br /> ''ho'' || {{Script|Tglg|\u1711\u1713}}\n|}\n|}\nNote that the first row of clusters (with ''virama'') \"+\" were a late addition to the original script introduced by Spaniards. And the other one \" \u1734\" was introduced by Antoon Postma. \n\n=== Punctuation and spelling ===\nBaybayin writing makes use of only two punctuation marks (originally only one), the Philippine single ({{Script|Tglg|\u1735}}) (acting today as a comma, or verse splitter in poetry) and double punctuation ({{Script|Tglg|\u1736}}) (main punctuation, acting today as a period or end of paragraph), which are similar to single and double danda signs in other Brahmic scripts. These signs (which may be presented vertically like Indic dandas, or slanted like forward slashes) are unified across Philippines scripts and were encoded by Unicode in the [[Hanunoo alphabet|Hanun\u00f3o script]] block.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unicode.org/versions/Unicode13.0.0/ch17.pdf#G26723|title=Chapter 17: Indonesia and Oceania, Philippine Scripts|publisher=Unicode Consortium|date=March 2020}}</ref> Space separation of words was historically not used on traditional supports, but is common today.\n\n=== Example sentences ===\n* {{Script|Tglg|\u170c\u170b\u1705\u1714 \u1707\u1712 \u1708\u1704\u1714\u1703\u1703\u1702\u1708\u170f\u1700\u1708\u1714\u1735 \u1700\u170c\u1714 \u170b\u1704\u1714 \u1709\u1703\u1711\u1712\u1708\u1711\u1713\u1708\u1714\u1736}}\n*: ''Yamang \u2018di nagkakaunawaan, ay mag-pakahinahon.''\n*: Remain calm in disagreements.\n* {{Script|Tglg|\u170b\u1704\u1714\u1706\u1708\u1712\u170b\u1714 \u1700\u170c\u1714 \u1707\u1712 \u170a\u1712\u1707\u1713\u1736}}\n*: ''Magtanim ay 'di bir\u00f2.''\n*: Planting is not a joke.\n*\u1700\u1705\u1714 \u1703\u170a\u1706\u1700\u1708\u1714 \u1700\u1705\u1714 \u1709\u1704\u1714\u1700\u1710 \u1708\u1705\u1714 \u170a\u170c\u1708\u1714\n\nAng k''abataan ang pag-asa ng bayan''\n\n<small>The youth is the hope of the country</small>\n\n<br />\n\n*{{Script|Tglg|\u170b\u170b\u1711\u170e\u1712\u1708\u1714 \u1703\u1712\u1706 \u1711\u1705\u1714\u1704\u1705\u1714 \u1710 \u1709\u1713\u170b\u1713\u1706\u1712 \u1700\u1705\u1714 \u170a\u1713\u1711\u1713\u1703\u1714 \u1703\u1713\u1736}}\n*:''M\u00e1mahalin kit\u00e1 hangg\u00e1ng sa pumut\u00ed ang buh\u00f3k ko.''\n*: I will love you until my hair turns white.\n\n=== Collation ===\n* In the ''[[Doctrina Christiana]]'', the letters of Baybayin were collated (without any connection with other similar script, except sorting vowels before consonants) as:\n*: '''A, U/O, I/E; Ha, Pa, Ka, Sa, La, Ta, Na, Ba, Ma, Ga, Da/Ra, Ya, NGa, Wa'''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/16119/16119-h/16119-h.htm#d0e129 |title=Doctrina Cristiana |website=Project Gutenberg}}</ref>\n* In Unicode the letters are collated in coherence with other Indic scripts, by phonetic proximity for consonnants:\n*: '''A, I/E, U/O; Ka, Ga, Nga; Ta, Da/Ra, Na; Pa, Ba, Ma; Ya, La, Wa, Sa, Ha'''.<ref name=\"UnicodeTagalog\">[https://www.unicode.org/charts/PDF/U1700.pdf Unicode Baybayin Tagalog variant]</ref>\n\n==Examples==\n\n=== The Lord's Prayer (''Ama Namin'') ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Baybayin script\n!scope=\"col\"| [[Latin script]]\n!scope=\"col\"| English <small>([[Book of Common Prayer#United States|1928 BCP]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://justus.anglican.org/resources/bcp/1928/Family_Prayer.htm|title=The 1928 Book of Common Prayer: Family Prayer|publisher=|accessdate=14 October 2016}}</ref><br /> (current [[Catholic Church in the Philippines|Filipino Catholic]] version<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/archive/ccc_css/archive/catechism/p4s2.htm#SECTION%20TWO%20THE%20LORDS%20PRAYER%20OUR%20FATHER!\u00bb Catechism of the Catholic Church]</ref>)</small>\n|-\n|\n<poem>\n{{Script|Tglg|\u1700\u170b \u1708\u170b\u1712\u1708\u1714\u1735 \u1710\u1713\u170b\u1710\u170e\u1705\u1712\u1706\u1714 \u1703\u1735}}\n{{Script|Tglg|\u1710\u170b\u1714\u170a\u1711\u1712\u1708\u1714 \u1700\u1705\u1714 \u1705\u170e\u1708\u1714 \u170b\u1713\u1736}}\n{{Script|Tglg|\u170b\u1709\u1710\u1700\u170b\u1712\u1708\u1714 \u1700\u1705\u1714 \u1703\u1711\u1707\u1712\u1700\u1708\u1714 \u170b\u1713\u1735}}\n{{Script|Tglg|\u1710\u1713\u1708\u1714\u1707\u1712\u1708\u1714 \u1700\u1705\u1714 \u170e\u1713\u1702\u170a\u1714 \u170b\u1713\u1735}}\n{{Script|Tglg|\u1707\u1712\u1706\u1713 \u1710 \u170e\u1713\u1709\u1735 \u1709\u1707 \u1708\u1705\u1714 \u1710 \u170e\u1705\u1712\u1706\u1714\u1736}}\n\n{{Script|Tglg|\u170a\u1712\u1704\u1714\u170c\u1708\u1714 \u170b\u1713 \u1703\u170b\u1712 \u1705\u170c\u1713\u1708\u1714 \u1708\u1705\u1714 \u1700\u170b\u1712\u1705\u1714 \u1703\u1703\u1708\u1712\u1708\u1714 \u1710 \u1700\u1707\u170f\u1714 \u1700\u1707\u170f\u1714\u1735}}\n{{Script|Tglg|\u1700\u1706\u1714 \u1709\u1706\u170f\u1707\u1712\u1708\u1714 \u170b\u1713 \u1703\u170b\u1712 \u1710 \u1700\u170b\u1712\u1705\u1714 \u170b\u1705 \u1710\u170e\u1735}}\n{{Script|Tglg|\u1709\u1707 \u1708\u1705\u1714 \u1709\u1704\u1714\u1709\u1709\u1706\u170f\u1707\u1714 \u1708\u170b\u1712\u1708\u1714 \u1710 \u170b\u1705 \u1708\u1704\u1714\u1703\u1703\u1710\u170e \u1710 \u1700\u170b\u1712\u1708\u1714\u1736}}\n\n{{Script|Tglg|\u1700\u1706\u1714 \u1711\u1713\u170f\u1704\u1714 \u170b\u1713 \u1703\u170b\u1712\u1705\u1714 \u1701\u1709\u1711\u1712\u1708\u1714\u1706\u1713\u170e\u1713\u1706\u1714 \u1710 \u1706\u1713\u1703\u1714\u1710\u1713\u1735}}\n{{Script|Tglg|\u1700\u1706\u1714 \u1701\u1700\u1707\u1714\u170c \u170b\u1713 \u1703\u170b\u1712 \u1710 \u170b\u1710\u170b\u1736 [[Amen|\u1710\u1712\u170c \u1708\u170f]]\u1736}}\n</poem>\n|\n<poem>\n''Ama namin, sumasalangit ka,''\n''Sambah\u00edn ang ngalan mo.''\n''Mapasaamin ang kahari\u00e1n mo,''\n''Sundin ang lo\u00f3b mo,''\n''Dito sa lup\u00e0, para nang sa langit.''\n\n''Bigy\u00e1n mo kam\u00ed ngay\u00f3n ng aming kakanin sa arau-arau;''\n''At patawarin mo kam\u00ed sa aming mga sala,''\n''Para nang pagpapatawad namin sa mga nagkakasala sa amin.''\n\n''At huw\u00e1g mo kam\u00edng ipahintulot sa tuks\u00f3,''\n''At iady\u00e2 mo kam\u00ed sa masama. [[Amen|Siya naw\u00e2]].''\n</poem>\n|\n<poem>\nOur Father who art in heaven,\nHallowed be Thy name.\nThy kingdom come,\nThy will be done,\nOn earth as it is in heaven.\n\nGive us this day our daily bread;\nAnd forgive us our trespasses,\nAs we forgive those who trespass against us.\n\nAnd lead us not into temptation,\nBut deliver us from evil. [[Amen]].\n</poem>\n|}\n\n===Universal Declaration of Human Rights===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Baybayin script\n!scope=\"col\"| Latin script\n!scope=\"col\"| English translation\n|-\n|\n{{Script|Tglg|\u1700\u1705\u1714 \u170e\u1711\u1706\u1714 \u1708\u1705\u1714 \u1706\u1702 \u1700\u170c\u1714  \u1701\u1710\u1712\u1708\u1712\u170e\u1705\u1714 \u1708 \u170b\u170e\u170c<br />\n\u1700\u1706\u1714 \u1709\u1708\u1714\u1706\u170c\u1714\u1709\u1708\u1714\u1706\u170c\u1714 \u1710 \u1703\u1707\u1705\u170e\u1708\u1714 \u1700\u1706\u1714 \u170b\u1705 \u1703\u1707\u1709\u1706\u1708\u1714\u1736}}\n\n{{Script|Tglg|\u1710\u1712\u170e \u1700\u170c\u1714 \u1709\u1712\u1708\u1704\u1714\u1703\u170e\u1713\u1702\u170a\u1708\u1714 \u1708\u1705\u1714 \u1703\u1706\u1713\u170f\u1712\u1707\u1708\u1714 \u1700\u1706\u1714 [[Bodhi|\u170a\u1713\u1707\u1714\u1711\u1712]]<br />\n\u1700\u1706\u1714 \u1707\u1709\u1706\u1714 \u170b\u1704\u1714\u1709\u170e\u1704\u170c\u1708\u1714 \u1700\u1705\u1714 \u1701\u1710\u1706\u1714 \u1701\u1710 \u1710 \u1707\u1712\u170f \u1708\u1705\u1714 \u1709\u1704\u1714\u1703\u1703\u1709\u1706\u1712\u1707\u1708\u1714\u1736}}\n|style=\"font-style:italic\"|\n{{lang|tl|Ang lahat ng tao'y isinilang na malaya}}<br />\n{{lang|tl|at pantay-pantay sa karangalan at mga karapatan.}}\n\n{{lang|tl|Sila'y pinagkalooban ng katuwiran at [[Bodhi|budhi]]}}<br />\n{{lang|tl|at dapat magpalagayan ang isa't isa sa diwa ng pagkakapatiran.}}\n|\nAll human beings are born free<br/>\nand equal in dignity and rights.\n\nThey are endowed with reason and [[Bodhi|conscience]]<br />\nand should act towards one another in a spirit of brotherhood.\n|}\n\n=== Motto of the Philippines ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Baybayin script\n!scope=\"col\"| Latin script\n!scope=\"col\"| English translation\n|-\n| {{Script|Tglg|\u170b\u1703\u1707\u1712\u170c\u1713\u1710\u1714\u1735<br /> \u170b\u1703\u1706\u1702\u1735<br /> \u170b\u1703\u1703\u170e\u1712\u1703\u1710\u1708\u1714\u1735 \u1700\u1706\u1714<br /> \u170b\u1703\u170a\u1708\u1714\u1710\u1736}}\n| {{lang|tl|Maka-Diyos,<br /> Maka-Tao,<br /> Makakalikasan, at<br /> Makabansa.}}\n| For God, <br> For People, <br> For Nature, and<br /> For Country.\n|-\n| {{Script|Tglg|\u1701\u1710\u1705\u1714 \u170a\u1708\u1714\u1710\u1735<br /> \u1701\u1710\u1705\u1714 \u1707\u1712\u170f\u1736}}\n| {{lang|tl|Isang Bansa,<br /> Isang Diwa}}\n| One Country,<br /> One Spirit.\n|}\n\n== Unicode ==\nBaybayin was added to the [[Unicode]] Standard in March, 2002 with the release of version 3.2.\n\n===Block===\nThe Unicode blocks for Baybayin covers Baybayin-Buhid, Baybayin-Hanuno\u00f3, Baybayin-Tagbanwa, and Baybayin-Tagalog.\n\n{{Main|Buhid (Unicode block)}}\n\nBaybayin-Buhid Unicode range: U+1740\u2013U+175F\n\n{{Unicode chart Buhid}}\n\n{{Main|Hanunoo (Unicode block)}}\n\nBaybayin-Hanuno\u00f3 Unicode range: U+1720\u2013U+173F\n\n{{Unicode chart Hanunoo}}\n\n{{Main|Tagbanwa (Unicode block)}}\n\nBaybayin-Tagbanwa Unicode range: U+1760\u2013U+177F\n\n{{Unicode chart Tagbanwa}}\n\n{{Main|Tagalog (Unicode block)}}\n\nBaybayin-Tagalog Unicode range: U+1700\u2013U+171F\n\n{{Unicode chart Tagalog}}\n\n== Keyboard ==\n\n=== Gboard ===\n[[File:Baybayin Keyboad by Gboard Screenshot.png|thumb|A screenshot image of the Baybayin keyboard on Gboard.]]\nThe [[virtual keyboard]] [[Mobile app|app]] [[Gboard]] developed by [[Google]] for [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[iOS]] devices was updated on August 1, 2019<ref>{{cite web |author=techmagus|title=Baybayin in Gboard App Now Available|url=https://techmagus.icu/baybayin-gboard-now-available/|access-date=2019-08-01}}</ref> its list of supported languages. This includes all Unicode Baybayin blocks namely: Baybayin-Buhid as \"Buhid\", Baybayin-Hanuno\u00f3 as \"Hanunuo\", Baybayin-Tagalog as \"Filipino (Baybayin), and Baybayin-Tagbanwa as \"Aborlan\".<ref>{{cite web |author=techmagus|title=Activate and Use Baybayin in Gboard|url=https://techmagus.icu/activate-baybayin-gboard/|access-date=2019-08-01}}</ref> The Baybayin-Tagalog (\"Filipino (Baybayin)\") keyboard layout was intuitively designed when pressing the character, vowel markers for e/i and o/u, as well as the virama (vowel sound cancellation) are shown in the middle of the keyboard layout.\n\n=== Philippines Unicode Keyboard Layout with Baybayin ===\nIt is possible to type Baybayin directly from the keyboard without the need to use online typepads. The Philippines Unicode Keyboard Layout<ref name=\"techmagus\">{{cite web |url=https://techmagus.icu/paninap-unicode-keyboard-layout/the-philippines-national-keyboard-layout/ |title=Philippines Unicode Keyboard Layout |website=techmagus\u2122}}</ref> includes different sets of Baybayin layout for different keyboard users: QWERTY, Capewell-Dvorak, Capewell-QWERF 2006, Colemak, and Dvorak, all available in Microsoft Windows and GNU/Linux 32-bit and 64-bit installations.\n\nThe keyboard layout with Baybayin can be downloaded at [https://bitbucket.org/paninap/ph-ukl/ this page].\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Baybayin}}\n*[[Ancient Philippine scripts]]\n*[[Buhid script]]\n*[[Filipino orthography]]\n*[[History of Indian influence on Southeast Asia]]\n*[[Hanunuo script]]\n*[[Kawi script]]\n*[[Kulitan alphabet]]\n*[[Laguna Copperplate Inscription]]\n*[[Old Tagalog]]\n*[[Suyat]]\n*[[Tagbanwa script]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140201135616/http://www.congress.gov.ph/download/basic_16/HB00160.pdf House Bill 160, aka ''National Script Act of 2011'']\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100821192259/http://www.mts.net/~pmorrow/bayeng1.htm ''Ang Baybayin'' by Paul Morrow]\n*[https://www.unicode.org/charts/PDF/U32-1700.pdf Unicode Tagalog Range 1700-171F (in PDF)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100809054112/http://www.mts.net/~pmorrow/paterno.htm Yet another Baybayin chart]\n*[http://www.eaglescorner.com/baybayin/baybayin.html Baybayin online translator]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071012072649/http://www.baybayin.com/how-to-write-baybayin-alibata/ Baybayin video tutorial]\n*[http://nordenx.blogspot.com/2012/05/baybayin-unicode-keyboard-layout.html Baybayin Unicode Keyboard Layout for Mac OSX]\n*[https://snoworld.one/-baybayin-typepad-01/ Snoworld\u2122's Baybayin Unicode Typepad]\n*[https://techmagus.icu/paninap-unicode-keyboard-layout/the-philippines-national-keyboard-layout/ Philippines Unicode Keyboard Layout with Baybayin, for Microsoft Windows and GNU/Linux both 32-bit and 64-bit]\n*[https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/baybayin-keyboard/fkbkkdokklbebkkifkoejdblhilfeghi Baybayin Keyboard extension for ChromeOS (Chromebooks)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110202182136/http://baybayinlibrary.com/ Online Baybayin Library]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110817111227/http://www.baybayinapp.com/ Baybayin mobile translator application ]\n*[http://nordenx.blogspot.com/p/baybayin-unicode-typepad.html Nordenx's Baybayin Unicode Typepad]\n*{{Cite book\n|last=Scott\n|first=William Henry\n|authorlink=William Henry Scott (historian)\n|title=Prehispanic Source Materials for the study of Philippine History\n|publisher=New Day Publishers\n|year=1984\n|isbn=971-10-0226-4\n|url=https://books.google.com/?id=bR2XAQAACAAJ\n|ref=harv\n|postscript=.\n}}\n\n===Font downloads===\n*[http://akopito.weebly.com/suwat-bisaya.html Badlit Script]\n*[http://nordenx.blogspot.com/ Baybayin Modern Fonts]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101231035914/http://www.baybayin.com/downloads/ Christian Cabuay's Baybayin Brush Font]\n*[http://paulmorrow.ca/fonts.htm Paul Morrow's Baybayin Fonts]\n*[http://unicode-table.com/en/sections/tagalog/ Tagalog \u2013 Unicode character table]\n{{Kawi family}}\n{{Philippine scripts}}\n{{list of writing systems}}\n{{ISO 15924/footer}}\n{{India-related topics in Philippines}}\n{{Symbols of the Philippines}}\n\n[[Category:Articles with inconsistent citation formats]]\n[[Category:Brahmic scripts]]\n[[Category:Philippine scripts]]\n[[Category:Tagalog language]]\n[[Category:Obsolete writing systems]]\n[[Category:Filipino language]]\n[[Category:India-related topics in the Philippines]]\n", "name_user": "Glennznl", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eModern Usage:Added picture of baybayin on a passport", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baybayin"}
{"title_page": "Priti Patel", "text_new": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Priti Patel\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Rt Hon Priti Patel MP crop 2.jpg\n| office = [[Home Secretary]]\n| primeminister = [[Boris Johnson]]\n| term_start = 24 July 2019\n| predecessor = [[Sajid Javid]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = [[Secretary of State for International Development]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start1 = 14 July 2016\n| term_end1 = 8 November 2017\n| predecessor1 = [[Justine Greening]]\n| successor1 = [[Penny Mordaunt]]\n| office2 = [[Department for Work and Pensions|Minister of State for Employment]]\n| primeminister2 = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start2 = 11 May 2015\n| term_end2 = 14 July 2016\n| predecessor2 = [[Esther McVey]]\n| successor2 = [[Damian Hinds]]\n| office3 = [[Exchequer Secretary to the Treasury]]\n| primeminister3 = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start3 = 15 July 2014\n| term_end3 = 11 May 2015\n| predecessor3 = [[David Gauke]]\n| successor3 = [[Damian Hinds]]\n| office4 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br> for [[Witham (UK Parliament constituency)|Witham]]\n| term_start4 = 6 May 2010\n| term_end4 = \n| predecessor4 = Constituency established\n| successor4 =\n| majority4 = 24,082 (48.8%)<ref name=BBC2019>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14001045|title=Witham|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=20 September 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_name = Priti Sushil Patel\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1972|3|29}}\n| birth_place = [[London]],  England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| signature = \n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] (before 1995; since 1997)\n| otherparty = [[Referendum Party|Referendum]] (1995\u20131997)\n| spouse = {{marriage|Alex Sawyer|2004}}\n| children = 1\n| alma_mater = [[Keele University]]<br />[[University of Essex]]\n| caption = Patel in 2020\n}}\n'''Priti Sushil Patel'''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201516/cmhansrd/cm150519/debtext/150519-0001.htm |title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 19 May 2015 (pt 0001) |publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom |date=19 May 2015 |accessdate=4 July 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404092037/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201516/cmhansrd/cm150519/debtext/150519-0001.htm |archivedate=4 April 2016}}</ref> (born 29 March 1972) is a British politician who has served as [[Secretary of State for the Home Department]] since 2019 and the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Witham (UK Parliament constituency)|Witham]] since [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]. She served as [[Secretary of State for International Development]] from 2016 to 2017. A member of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]], she is ideologically positioned on the party's right wing and considers herself to be a [[Thatcherism|Thatcherite]].\n\nPatel was born in London to a [[Indians in Uganda|Ugandan-Indian]] family. She was educated at [[Keele University]] and the [[University of Essex]]. Inspired to get involved in politics by Conservative Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]], she was initially involved with the [[Referendum Party]] before switching allegiance to the Conservatives. She worked for the public-relations consultancy firm [[Weber Shandwick]] for several years, as part of which she lobbied for the tobacco and alcohol industries. Intending to switch to a political career, she unsuccessfully contested [[Nottingham North (UK Parliament constituency)|Nottingham North]] at the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]]. After [[David Cameron]] became [[party leader|Conservative leader]], he recommended Patel for the party's \"[[Conservative A-List|A-List]]\" of [[prospective parliamentary candidate|prospective candidates]]. She was first elected MP for Witham, a Conservative [[safe seat]] in [[Essex]], at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], before being re-elected in [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]], [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]] and [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]. Under Cameron's government, Patel was appointed [[Department of Work and Pensions|Minister of State for Employment]] and served as vice-chair of the [[Conservative Friends of Israel]]. She attracted attention for her [[social conservatism|socially conservative]] stances.\n\nA longstanding [[Euroscepticism|Eurosceptic]], Patel was a leading figure in the [[Vote Leave]] campaign during the build-up to the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum on UK membership]] of the [[European Union]]. Following Cameron's resignation, Patel backed [[Theresa May]] as Conservative leader; May subsequently appointed Patel [[Secretary of State for International Development]]. In 2017 she was involved in a political scandal involving unauthorised meetings with the [[Government of Israel]], ending her tenure as International Development Secretary. Under [[Boris Johnson]]'s premiership, she became Home Secretary in 2019, the first ethnic minority woman to hold the office.\n\nPatel has been criticised by political opponents for defending the tobacco and alcohol industries,<ref name=\":3\" /> and for advocating threatening the [[Republic of Ireland]] with food shortages during Brexit negotiations.<ref name=\"food\">{{cite news |last1=Kentish |first1=Benjamin |title=Britain should use risk of economic damage Ireland to get better Brexit deal, suggests Priti Patel |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-ireland-food-shortages-threat-risk-priti-patel-negotiate-better-deal-a8672326.html |work=The Independent |date=7 December 2018 |language=en |quote=Ms Patel said her comments had been taken out of context and that she had not referred specifically to the risk of food shortages. Rather, she said, she had been arguing that \"the consequences of not gettin' a favourable deal for all should help to focus minds\".}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Learmonth |first1=Andrew |title=Fury at Tory's plan to use food shortages as leverage in Brexit talks |url=https://www.thenational.scot/news/17284900.priti-patel-suggests-using-food-shortage-threat-in-brexit-talks/ |work=[[The National (Scotland)|The National]] |date=8 December 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Patel said her comments were \"taken out of context\" and that she did not refer specifically to the risk of food shortages.<ref name=\"food\"/><ref name=\"irish\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-46488479|title=Irish 'food shortage' comments condemned|date=7 December 2018|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nPriti Patel was born on 29 March 1972 to Sushil and Anjana Patel in London.<ref name=BME>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-43350527|title=BME label insulting, says ex-minister Priti Patel|work=BBC News|date=9 March 2018|accessdate=10 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/nov/08/priti-patel-an-outspoken-brexiter-who-went-too-quietly-to-israel|title=Priti Patel: an outspoken Brexiter who went too quietly to Israel|first=Anushka|last=Asthana|date=8 November 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=13 November 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171113054003/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/nov/08/priti-patel-an-outspoken-brexiter-who-went-too-quietly-to-israel|archivedate=13 November 2017}}</ref> Her paternal grandparents were born in [[Tarapur, Gujarat]], before emigrating to [[Uganda]], and establishing a shop in [[Kampala]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/explained/who-is-priti-patel-britains-new-home-secretary-5852090/|title=Explained: Who's Priti Patel, Britain's new Home Secretary?|date=28 July 2019|work=The Indian Express}}</ref> In the 1960s her parents emigrated to the UK and settled in [[Hertfordshire, England|Hertfordshire]].<ref name=ibtnew>{{cite news |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/priti-patel-mp-new-face-britains-conservative-party-1000142 |title=Priti Patel, MP: The New Face Of Britain's Conservative Party |work=International Business Times |date=8 January 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530164139/http://www.ibtimes.com/priti-patel-mp-new-face-britains-conservative-party-1000142 |archivedate=30 May 2015  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.eadt.co.uk/news/east-meets-westminster-young-asian-and-female-essex-mp-priti-patel-is-modern-face-of-the-tories-1-1447039|work=Eastern Anglia Daily Times|date=16 July 2012|accessdate=10 February 2020|title=East meets Westminster: Young, Asian and female - Essex MP Priti Patel is modern face of the Tories}}</ref> They established a chain of [[Newsagent's shop|newsagents]] in London and the [[South East of England]].<ref name=totalpolitics/><ref name=Warrell>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/52fbc7c8-b50d-11e9-8cb2-799a3a8cf37b|title=How radical will Priti Patel be at the UK Home Office?|work=Financial Times|last1=Warrell|first1=Helen|last2=Staton|first2=Bethan|date=4 August 2019}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nPatel attended [[Watford Grammar School for Girls]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Hope|first=Christopher |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/10969676/Pen-portraits-of-the-10-Conservative-women-ministers-who-were-promoted-in-the-reshuffle.html|title=Pen portraits of the 10 Conservative women ministers who were promoted in the reshuffle|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=15 July 2014|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517122250/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/10969676/Pen-portraits-of-the-10-Conservative-women-ministers-who-were-promoted-in-the-reshuffle.html|archivedate=17 May 2017}}</ref> before studying Economics at [[Keele University]] and then pursuing postgraduate studies in British Government and Politics at the [[University of Essex]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-28292058 |title=The Conservative women on the rise in Cameron's reshuffle |work=[[BBC News]] |date=15 July 2014 |accessdate=30 May 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150903230217/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-28292058 |archivedate=3 September 2015  }}</ref><ref name=profile>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-41913203|title=Profile: Priti Patel|date=8 November 2017 |publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109081403/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-41913203 |archivedate=9 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Conservative Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]] became her political heroine: according to Patel, she \"had a unique ability to understand what made people tick, households tick and businesses tick. Managin' the economy, balancin' the books and makin' decisions \u2013 not purchasin' things the country couldn't afford\".<ref name=totalpolitics/> She first joined the Conservative Party as a teenager, when [[John Major]] was [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]].<ref name=ibtnew />\n\n==Early career==\nAfter graduating, Patel became an intern at Conservative Central Office (now known as [[Conservative Campaign Headquarters]]), having been selected by [[Andrew Lansley]] (then Head of the [[Conservative Research Department]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/home-affairs/house/71738/priti-please|title=Priti, please|last=Waugh|first=Paul|date=30 January 2014|accessdate=14 September 2019|publisher=Politics Home}}</ref> From 1995 to 1997, Patel headed the press office of the [[Referendum Party]], a single-issue Eurosceptic party.<ref name=profile/>\n\nIn 1997, Patel left to join the Conservative Party having been offered a post to work for the new leader [[William Hague]] in his press office, dealing with media relations in London and the [[South East of England]].<ref name = \"QT2007 summary\">{{cite news | title = This week's panel | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/6443391.stm | date = 15 March 2007 | work = Question Time | publisher = BBC | accessdate = 31 May 2015 }}</ref> In August 2003, the ''[[Financial Times]]'' published an article citing quotes from Patel and alleging that \"[[Racism|racist]] attitudes\" persisted in the Conservative Party, and that \"there's a lot of bigotry around\".<ref name=\"BBC A-List\">{{cite news|last=Brant |first=Robin |date=4 December 2006 |title=A year on, has the A-list worked? |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6206132.stm |publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=31 May 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808102841/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6206132.stm |archivedate=8 August 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Patel wrote to the ''FT'' countering its article stating that her comments had been misinterpreted to imply that she had been blocked as a [[prospective parliamentary candidate|party candidate]] because of her [[ethnicity]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/question_time/6443391.stm|title=This week's panel|date=15 March 2007|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000 Patel left the employment of the Conservative Party to work for [[Weber Shandwick]], a [[public relations|PR]] consulting firm.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prweek.com/channel/PublicAffairs/article/1002450/many-lobbyists-win-seats-majority-decreased |title=Many lobbyists win seats but some see majority decreased|first=David|last=Singleton|work=PR Week |date=11 May 2010 |accessdate=22 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807140140/http://www.prweek.com/channel/PublicAffairs/article/1002450/many-lobbyists-win-seats-majority-decreased |archivedate=7 August 2011}}</ref> According to an investigative article published by ''[[The Guardian]]'' in May 2015, Patel was one of seven Weber Shandwick employees who worked on [[British American Tobacco]] (BAT) \u2013 a major account. The team had been tasked with helping BAT manage the company's public image during the controversy around the Burma factory being used as source of funds by its military dictatorship and poor payment to factory workers. The crisis eventually ended with BAT pulling out of Burma in 2003. The article went on to quote BAT employees who felt that though a majority of Weber Shandwick employees were uncomfortable working with them, Patel's group was fairly relaxed. The article also quoted internal documents specifying that a part of Patel's job was also to lobby [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]]s against EU tobacco regulations. She worked for Weber Shandwick for three years.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jamie|last=Doward |date=30 May 2015 |title=Minister worked as spin doctor for tobacco giant that paid workers \u00a315 a month |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/may/30/priti-patel-worked-as-spin-doctor-tobacco-firm-burma-scandal |work=The Guardian |accessdate=30 May 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530154927/http://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/may/30/priti-patel-worked-as-spin-doctor-tobacco-firm-burma-scandal |archivedate=30 May 2015  }}</ref>\n\nPatel then moved to the British multinational alcoholic beverages company, [[Diageo]], and worked in [[Corporate communication|corporate relations]] between 2003 and 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.prweek.com/article/771926/tory-rising-star-snared-ws|title=Tory rising star is snared by WS|date=6 December 2007|access-date=10 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110172111/https://www.prweek.com/article/771926/tory-rising-star-snared-ws|archivedate=10 November 2017|work=PR Week}}</ref> In 2007, she rejoined Weber Shandwick as Director of Corporate and Public Affairs practices. According to their press release, during her time at Diageo, Patel had \"worked on international public policy issues related to the wider impact of alcohol in society.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Tory rising star returns to Weber Shandwick|url=http://www.webershandwick.co.uk/homepage-sections/what-we-are-up-to/157|publisher=Weber Shandwick|accessdate=30 May 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080116141016/http://www.webershandwick.co.uk/homepage-sections/what-we-are-up-to/157|archivedate=16 January 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\n\n===Member of Parliament for Witham: 2010\u2013present===\n[[File:Panel for 'Britannia Unchained' (8077416892).jpg|thumb|right|Patel on the panel of \"Britannia Unchained\"]]\n\nIn the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]], she stood as the Conservative candidate for [[Nottingham North (UK Parliament constituency)|Nottingham North]], losing to the incumbent [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] MP [[Graham Allen (politician)|Graham Allen]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Natalie|last=Fahy|url=http://www.nottinghampost.com/Election-results-Nottingham-North-2001-2005-2010/story-26449521-detail/story.html|title=Election results for Nottingham North from 2001, 2005 and 2010 |work=Nottingham Post|date=6 May 2015 |accessdate=4 July 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706182532/http://www.nottinghampost.com/Election-results-Nottingham-North-2001-2005-2010/story-26449521-detail/story.html |archivedate=6 July 2015  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/vote2005/html/439.stm|title=Result: Nottingham North |publisher=BBC News|accessdate=14 September 2019|date=6 May 2005}}</ref> Despite her unsuccessful parliamentary campaign, Patel was identified as a promising candidate by new party leader David Cameron, and was offered a place on the \"[[Conservative A-List|A-List]]\" of Conservative [[prospective parliamentary candidate]]s (PPC).<ref name = \"BBC A-List\"/> In November 2006, she was adopted as the PPC for the notionally safe Conservative seat of [[Witham (UK Parliament constituency)|Witham]] \u2014 a new constituency in central Essex created after a [[Boundary Commissions (United Kingdom)|boundary review]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/ |title=Priti Patel takes Witham by storm |work=East Anglian Daily Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051210052439/http://www.eadt.co.uk/ |archivedate=10 December 2005 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Priti Patel takes Witham by storm|first=Graham|last=Dines|date=21 November 2006|work=Eastern Daily Press|url=http://www.edp24.co.uk/news/politics/priti_patel_takes_witham_by_storm_1_78129|accessdate=12 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130509232612/http://www.edp24.co.uk/news/politics/priti_patel_takes_witham_by_storm_1_78129|archivedate=9 May 2013}}</ref> \u2014 before gaining a majority of 15,196 at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]]. She was drafted into the [[Number 10 Policy Unit]] in October 2013,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/coffeehouse/2013/10/new-number-10-policy-board-announced/|title=New Number 10 policy board announced|work=The Spectator|date=15 October 2013|accessdate=15 July 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140105195313/http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/coffeehouse/2013/10/new-number-10-policy-board-announced/|archivedate=5 January 2014}}</ref> and was promoted as [[Exchequer Secretary to the Treasury]] the following summer.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/priti-patel-cabinet-home-secretary-boris-views-beliefs-israel-ireland-death-penalty-a9018616.html|work=The Independent|title=Priti Patel: Disgraced former minister who previously supported death penalty named home secretary by Boris Johnson|date=24 July 2019|accessdate=10 February 2020|last=Cockburn|first=Harry}}</ref>\n\nAlong with fellow Conservative MPs [[Kwasi Kwarteng]], [[Dominic Raab]], [[Chris Skidmore]] and [[Liz Truss]], Patel was considered one of the \"Class of 2010\" who represented the party's \"new Right\".<ref name=week/> Together they co-authored ''[[Britannia Unchained]]'', a book published in 2012. This work was critical of levels of workplace productivity in the UK, making the controversial statement that \"once they enter the workplace, the British are among the worst idlers in the world\". The authors suggested that to change this situation, the UK should reduce the size of the [[welfare state]] and seek to emulate the working conditions in countries like Singapore, Hong Kong, and South Korea rather than those of other European nations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/tackle-lazy-britain-fellow-tories-tell-david-cameron-8056787.html|title=Tackle 'lazy' Britain, fellow Tories tell David Cameron|website=London Evening Standard|date=17 August 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161207135125/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/tackle-lazy-britain-fellow-tories-tell-david-cameron-8056787.html|archivedate=7 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Randeep|last=Ramesh|date=17 August 2012 |title=Tory young bloods say Britons are idlers who need to emulate Asia |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/aug/17/tory-backbenchers-urge-welfare-reforms |work=The Guardian |accessdate=31 May 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312145055/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/aug/17/tory-backbenchers-urge-welfare-reforms |archivedate=12 March 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref> In the same year, Patel was elected on to the executive of the [[1922 Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-18093877|website=BBC News|date=17 May 2012|accessdate=22 September 2019|title=New faces elected on to influential Conservative 1922 committee}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, Patel criticised the plan of the [[Academies Enterprise Trust]] to merge the New Rickstones and Maltings Academies, claiming that to do so would be detrimental to school standards.<ref>{{cite news|first=Will|last=Lodge|title=Witham: MP Priti Patel voices opposition to merger of Maltings and New Rickstones Academies |website=East Anglian Daily News |date=15 October 2014 |url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/witham_mp_priti_patel_voices_opposition_to_merger_of_maltings_and_new_rickstones_academies_1_3807267 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150810073826/http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/witham_mp_priti_patel_voices_opposition_to_merger_of_maltings_and_new_rickstones_academies_1_3807267 |archivedate=10 August 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Patel lodged a complaint with the [[BBC]] alleging one-sided coverage critical of [[Narendra Modi]] on the eve of [[Prime Minister of India|his]] victory in [[2014 Indian general elections|2014 Indian elections]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/nri/Indian-origin-MP-takes-BBCs-Modi-coverage-complaint-to-UK-ministry/articleshow/37035502.cms|title=Indian-origin MP takes BBC's 'Modi coverage' complaint to UK ministry|work=The Times of India|date=22 June 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140622194325/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/nri/Indian-origin-MP-takes-BBCs-Modi-coverage-complaint-to-UK-ministry/articleshow/37035502.cms|archivedate=22 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/cameron-aide-takes-on-bbc-over-modi-india-image/article1-1231733.aspx|title=British PM Cameron's aide takes on BBC over critical comments against Modi|work=Hindustan Times|date=20 June 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140623061057/http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/cameron-aide-takes-on-bbc-over-modi-india-image/article1-1231733.aspx|archivedate=23 June 2014}}</ref> In January 2015, Patel was presented with a \"Jewels of Gujarat\" award in [[Ahmedabad]], India, and in the city she gave a keynote speech at the Gujarat Chamber of Commerce.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/world-location-news/uk-minister-priti-patel-honoured-at-jewels-of-gujarat-reception|title=UK Minister Priti Patel honoured at 'Jewels of Gujarat' reception|publisher=British High Commission, New Delhi|date=7 January 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402122240/https://www.gov.uk/government/world-location-news/uk-minister-priti-patel-honoured-at-jewels-of-gujarat-reception|archivedate=2 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|general election of May 2015]] \u2014 a Conservative victory \u2014 Patel retained her parliamentary seat with 27,123 votes, increasing her majority by 4,358.<ref>{{cite news|first=Will|last=Lodge |title=Election 2015: Priti Patel extends majority for Conservatives in Witham |date=8 May 2015 |website=East Anglian Daily Times |url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/election_2015_priti_patel_extends_majority_for_conservatives_in_witham_1_4065630 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150718234906/http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/election_2015_priti_patel_extends_majority_for_conservatives_in_witham_1_4065630 |archivedate=18 July 2015  }}</ref> During the campaign, she had criticised [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] rival John Clarke for referring to her as a \"sexy [[Bond villain]]\" and a \"[[village idiot]]\" on [[social media]]; he apologised.<ref>{{cite news|first=Annabelle|last=Dickson |date=24 March 2015 |website=East Anglian Daily Times |title=Tories want Labour election candidate who described Witham MP Priti Patel as 'sexy Bond villain' to be axed |url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/tories_want_labour_election_candidate_who_described_witham_mp_priti_patel_as_sexy_bond_villain_to_be_axed_1_4006347 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150328060608/http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/tories_want_labour_election_candidate_who_described_witham_mp_priti_patel_as_sexy_bond_villain_to_be_axed_1_4006347 |archivedate=28 March 2015  }}</ref> After the election, Patel rose to Cabinet-level as [[Minister of State|Minister of State for Employment]] in the [[Department for Work and Pensions]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2015-05-11/priti-patel-appointed-as-employment-minister/|title=Priti Patel appointed as Employment Minister|publisher=ITV News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150514021143/http://www.itv.com/news/update/2015-05-11/priti-patel-appointed-as-employment-minister/|archivedate=14 May 2015}}</ref> and was sworn of the [[Privy Council]] on 14 May 2015. \n\nIn October 2015 a junior employee at the [[Department for Work and Pensions]] was dismissed from her role. In response, the employee brought a formal complaint of bullying and harassment against the department, including Patel. In 2017 a settlement was reached for \u00a325,000 after the member of staff threatened to bring a legal claim of bullying, harassment and discrimination on the grounds of race and disability against the department and Patel.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Titheradge|first=Rianna Croxford and Noel|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51705069|title=Patel aide got \u00a325k payout 'over bullying'|date=2020-03-03|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-03|language=en-GB}}</ref>  \n\nIn December 2015, Patel voted to support Cameron's planned bombing of [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] targets in Syria.<ref>{{cite news|first=Annabelle|last=Dickson |title=Prime Minister given backing to extend air strikes to Syria |date=2 December 2015 |website=East Anglian Daily Times |url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/prime_minister_given_backing_to_extend_air_strikes_to_syria_how_did_your_mp_vote_1_4334448 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151203215002/http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/prime_minister_given_backing_to_extend_air_strikes_to_syria_how_did_your_mp_vote_1_4334448 |archivedate=3 December 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n===Brexit campaign: 2015\u20132016===\nFollowing Cameron's announcement of [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|a referendum on the UK's continuing membership]] of the [[European Union]] (EU), Patel was widely touted as a likely \"poster girl\" for the [[Vote Leave]] campaign.<ref name=\"ibtimes_iansilvera\">{{cite news|first=Ian|last=Silvera|title=Priti Patel: Who is the top Tory right-winger tipped to be the face of the Brexit campaign? |date=8 February 2016 |website=International Business Times |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/priti-patel-who-top-tory-right-winger-tipped-be-face-brexit-campaign-1542619 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160209093440/http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/priti-patel-who-top-tory-right-winger-tipped-be-face-brexit-campaign-1542619 |archivedate=9 February 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Patel said that the EU is \"undemocratic and interferes too much in our daily lives\". She publicly stated that immigration from elsewhere in the EU was overstretching the resources of UK schools.<ref>{{cite news |first=Rowena|last=Mason|title=Priti Patel warns of EU migration threat to UK class sizes |work=The Guardian |date=21 June 2016 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/21/priti-patel-warns-of-eu-migration-threat-to-uk-class-sizes |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011022319/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/21/priti-patel-warns-of-eu-migration-threat-to-uk-class-sizes |archivedate=11 October 2016  }}</ref> She helped to launch the Women For Britain campaign for anti-EU women; at their launch party, she compared their campaign with that of [[Emmeline Pankhurst]] and the [[Suffragettes]], for which she was criticised by Emmeline's great-granddaughter Helen Pankhurst.<ref>{{cite news |first=Annabelle|last=Dickson|work=East Anglian Daily Times |date=8 March 2016 |title=Essex MP under fire for likening women who campaign to leave the European Union to the suffragettes |url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/essex_mp_under_fire_for_likening_women_who_campaign_to_leave_the_european_union_to_the_suffragettes_1_4447801 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006143717/http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/essex_mp_under_fire_for_likening_women_who_campaign_to_leave_the_european_union_to_the_suffragettes_1_4447801 |archivedate=6 October 2016  }}</ref>\n\nFollowing the success of the \"[[Brexit|Leave]]\" vote in the EU referendum, Cameron resigned, resulting in a leadership contest within the party. Patel openly supported [[Theresa May]] as his successor, claiming that she had the \"strength and experience\" for the job, while arguing that May's main challenger [[Andrea Leadsom]] would prove too divisive to win a general election.<ref>{{cite news|title=Priti Patel: Andrea Leadsom could become a Tory Corbyn |first=Tim|last=Ross |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=9 July 2016 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/09/priti-patel-interview-andrea-leadsom-could-become-a-tory-corbyn/ |archivedate=9 July 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160709222928/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/09/priti-patel-interview-andrea-leadsom-could-become-a-tory-corbyn/  }}</ref> In November 2017, Patel was critical of the UK government [[Brexit negotiations]] and stated: \"I would have told the EU in particular to sod off with their excessive financial demands\".<ref>{{cite news|date=27 November 2017|title=I would have told the EU to sod off over Brexit divorce bill, Priti Patel says|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/11/27/would-have-told-eu-sod-brexit-divorce-bill-priti-patel-says/|archivedate=2 December 2017|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=2 December 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202042938/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/11/27/would-have-told-eu-sod-brexit-divorce-bill-priti-patel-says/}}</ref>\n\n===Secretary of State for International Development: 2016\u20132017===\n\n[[File:Narendra Modi is greeted by British MP Priti Patel after arriving at Heathrow Airport.jpg|thumb|Patel greeting Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] at [[Heathrow Airport]] on 12 November 2015|alt=]]\n\nAfter becoming Prime Minister, in July 2016 May appointed Patel to the position of International Development Secretary. Patel described herself as being \"delighted\" with the post despite a statement made in 2013 suggesting that the Department for International Development (DFID) should be scrapped and replaced with a Department for International Trade and Development.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/new-international-development-secretary-priti-patel-called-for-department-for-international-a7137331.html |title=The new International Development Secretary wanted to scrap what is now her department |website=The Independent|date=14 July 2016|first=Jon|last=Stone|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628034520/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/new-international-development-secretary-priti-patel-called-for-department-for-international-a7137331.html |archivedate=28 June 2017}}</ref>\nMany staff at the department were concerned about Patel's appointment, both because of her support for Brexit and because of her longstanding scepticism regarding international development and aid spending.<ref>{{cite news |title=Dfid officials are worried about Priti Patel, but it's Brexit they should be frightened of |date=20 September 2016 |first=Stephen|last=Bush|website=New Statesman |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/staggers/2016/09/dfid-officials-are-worried-about-priti-patel-its-brexit-they-should-be |accessdate=20 September 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920154716/http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/staggers/2016/09/dfid-officials-are-worried-about-priti-patel-its-brexit-they-should-be |archivedate=20 September 2016  }}</ref>\n\nOn taking the position, Patel stated that too much UK aid was wasted or spent inappropriately, declaring that she would adopt an approach rooted in \"core Conservative principles\" and emphasise international development through trade as opposed to aid.<ref>{{cite news |first=Ben|last=Quinn|title=Priti Patel plans foreign aid overhaul based on 'core Tory values' |website=The Guardian |date=14 September 2016 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/sep/14/priti-patel-plans-foreign-aid-overhaul-based-on-core-tory-values |accessdate=20 September 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920081621/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/sep/14/priti-patel-plans-foreign-aid-overhaul-based-on-core-tory-values |archivedate=20 September 2016  }}</ref> In September, Patel announced that the UK would contribute \u00a31.1&nbsp;billion to a global aid fund used to combat [[malaria]], [[tuberculosis]], and [[HIV/AIDS]], but added that any further aid deals would include \"performance agreements\" meaning that the British Government could reduce aid by 10% if specific criteria were not met by the recipient country.<ref>{{cite news|first=Peter|last=Dominiczak|title=Britain will withhold foreign aid money if performance countries' targets are not met  |date=18 September 2016 |work=The Daily Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/09/18/foreign-aid-money-to-be-limited-if-performance-targets-are-not-m/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919130230/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/09/18/foreign-aid-money-to-be-limited-if-performance-targets-are-not-m/ |archivedate=19 September 2016 }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016 she expressed opposition to the construction of 28 [[affordable housing|affordable home]]s at the Lakelands development in [[Stanway, Essex|Stanway]], referring to it as an \"unacceptable loss of open space\" and criticising [[Colchester Borough Council]] for permitting it.<ref>{{cite web|first=Matt|last=Stott|title=Witham MP Priti Patel labels Colchester Borough Council 'rotten' in Stanway housing development dispute |date=6 September 2016 |website=East Anglian Daily Times |url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/witham_mp_priti_patel_labels_colchester_borough_council_rotten_in_stanway_housing_development_dispute_1_4685526 |accessdate=20 September 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160906092140/http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/witham_mp_priti_patel_labels_colchester_borough_council_rotten_in_stanway_housing_development_dispute_1_4685526 |archivedate=6 September 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> That same month, the council's chief executive Adrian Pritchard issued a complaint against Patel, claiming that she had acted \"inappropriately\" in urging [[Sajid Javid]] to approve the construction of an out-of-town [[retail park]] after it had already been rejected by Colchester Council.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ryan|last=Jennings|title=Council claims MP acted 'inappropriately' in Tollgate planning row|work=The Daily Gazette|date=20 September 2016|url=http://www.gazette-news.co.uk/news/14752217.Council_claims_MP_acted__inappropriately__in_Tollgate_planning_row/|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921195321/http://www.gazette-news.co.uk/news/14752217.Council_claims_MP_acted__inappropriately__in_Tollgate_planning_row/|archivedate=21 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:The Secretary of State for International Development, United Kingdom, Ms. Priti Patel calling on the Prime Minister, Shri Narendra Modi, in New Delhi on August 13, 2016.jpg|thumb|left|Patel with Modi in 2016]]\n\nAlso in September, proposals were put forward for a change to the boundaries of parliamentary constituencies across the UK. As a result of the plans, Patel's seat of Witham would be merged with neighbouring [[Maldon (UK Parliament constituency)|Maldon]]. This would potentially require her to compete against Maldon MP [[John Whittingdale]] for the new seat of Witham and Maldon.<ref>{{cite news|first=Matt|last=Stott|title=Witham MP Priti Patel and Maldon MP John Whittingdale set to fight over merged seat at 2020 General Election |date=13 September 2016 |website=East Anglian Daily Times |url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/witham_mp_priti_patel_and_maldon_mp_john_whittingdale_set_to_fight_over_merged_seat_at_2020_general_election_1_4693809 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917004223/http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/witham_mp_priti_patel_and_maldon_mp_john_whittingdale_set_to_fight_over_merged_seat_at_2020_general_election_1_4693809 |archivedate=17 September 2016  }}</ref>\n\nPatel was critical of the UK's decision to invest DFID funds to support the [[Palestinian territories]] through [[UN]] agencies and the [[Palestinian Authority]]. In October 2016 she ordered a review of the funding procedure, temporarily freezing approximately a third of Britain's aid to the Palestinians during the review. In December 2016, DFID announced significant changes concerning future funding for the Palestinian Authority. DFID stated that future aid would go \"solely to vital health and education services, in order to meet the immediate needs of the Palestinian people and maximise value for money.\" This move was widely supported by Jewish groups, including the [[Jewish Leadership Council]] and the [[Zionist Federation of Great Britain and Ireland|Zionist Federation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/uk-cracks-down-on-palestinian-aid-following-three-month-freeze/|title=UK cracks down on Palestinian aid following three-month freeze|last=Frazer|first=Jenni|date=16 December 2016|website=Jewish News Online|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109025819/http://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/uk-cracks-down-on-palestinian-aid-following-three-month-freeze/|archivedate=9 November 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=8 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-41853561|title=Priti Patel held undisclosed meetings in Israel|date=3 November 2017|publisher=BBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171105055901/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-41853561|archivedate=5 November 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=8 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Patel and the Labour MEP [[Neena Gill]] were the two UK winners of the [[Pravasi Bharatiya Samman]], the highest honour that the Indian government gives to [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|non-resident Indians or people of Indian origin]]. She was given the award for her public service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mea.gov.in/press-releases.htm?dtl/27911/Pravasi+Bharatiya+Samman+Awards2017|title=Pravasi Bharatiya Samman Awards-2017|publisher=[[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Ministry of External Affairs]]|date=9 January 2017|accessdate=15 September 2019}}</ref> In the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|June snap general election]], she was re-elected as MP for Witham with a majority 18,646 votes.<ref name=BBC2019/>\n\nIn March 2020, it was reported that while serving as International Development Secretary Patel was alleged to have \u201charassed and belittled\u201d staff in her private office in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Syal|first=Rajeev|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/mar/03/dominic-cummings-fostering-culture-of-bullying-says-labour|title=Priti Patel accused of bullying a third senior civil servant|date=2020-03-04|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-04|last2=Stewart|first2=Heather|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n====Meetings with Israeli officials and resignation====\nOn 3 November 2017, the [[BBC]]'s Diplomatic correspondent [[James Landale]] broke the news that Patel had held meetings in Israel in August 2017 without telling the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Office]]. She was accompanied by [[Stuart Polak, Baron Polak|Lord Polak]], honorary president of [[Conservative Friends of Israel]] (CFI). The meetings, up to a dozen in number, took place while Patel was on a \"private holiday\". Patel met [[Yair Lapid]], the leader of Israel's centrist [[Yesh Atid]] party, and reportedly made visits to several organisations where official departmental business was discussed. The BBC reported that \"According to one source, at least one of the meetings was held at the suggestion of the Israeli ambassador to London. In contrast, British diplomats in Israel were not informed about Ms Patel's plans.\"<ref name=\"bbc_jameslandel\">{{cite news|last=Landale|first=James|authorlink=James Landale|title=Priti Patel held undisclosed meetings in Israel|date=3 November 2017|publisher=[[BBC News]]|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-41853561|accessdate=7 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171105055901/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-41853561|archivedate=5 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIt was also reported that, following the meetings, Patel had recommended that the Department for International Development give international aid money to field hospitals run by the Israeli army in the [[Golan Heights]].  Although these hospitals have been described by the British Prime Minister's official spokesman as \"provid[ing] medical support for Syrian refugees\",<ref name=\"telearmy\">{{cite news |date= 7 November 2017 |title= Priti Patel suggested UK should 'give aid to Israeli army' after secret meeting with Benjamin Netanyahu |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/11/07/priti-patel-suggested-uk-should-give-aid-israeli-army-secret/ |work= [[The Daily Telegraph]] |access-date= 7 November 2017 |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20171107195759/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/11/07/priti-patel-suggested-uk-should-give-aid-israeli-army-secret/ |archivedate= 7 November 2017 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> Israeli officials have refused to identify who they treat in them, and whether they are regime forces, rebels or civilians.<ref name=interacting>{{Cite news |last= Lewis |first= Avi |date= 7 December 2014 |title= UN: Israel interacting with rebels on Syrian border |url= https://www.timesofisrael.com/un-israel-interacting-with-rebels-on-syrian-border/ |website= [[The Times of Israel]] |access-date= 10 November 2017 |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170619063953/http://www.timesofisrael.com/un-israel-interacting-with-rebels-on-syrian-border/ |archivedate= 19 June 2017 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> Western media reports suggest that Israel is aiding and funding Syrian opposition organisations in the [[Syrian civil war]].<ref>\"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/israel-giving-secret-aid-syrian-rebels-bashar-al-assad-golah-heights-hezbollah-fursan-al-joulan-a7797151.html Israel \u2018giving secret aid to Syrian rebels\u2019, report says] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827212558/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/israel-giving-secret-aid-syrian-rebels-bashar-al-assad-golah-heights-hezbollah-fursan-al-joulan-a7797151.html |date=27 August 2017 }}\" by Bethan McKernan, ''[[The Independent]]'', 19 June 2017</ref><ref>\"[https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-gives-secret-aid-to-syrian-rebels-1497813430 Israel Gives Secret Aid to Syrian Rebels] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628103834/https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-gives-secret-aid-to-syrian-rebels-1497813430 |date=28 June 2017 }}\" by Rory Jones, Noam Raydan, and Suha Ma'ayeh, ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', 18 June 2017</ref>\n\nOn 4 November 2017, in an interview with ''[[The Guardian]]'', Patel stated<blockquote>Boris [Johnson] knew about the visit. The point is that the Foreign Office did know about this, Boris knew about [the trip]. I went out there, I paid for it. And there is nothing else to this. It is quite extraordinary. It is for the Foreign Office to go away and explain themselves. The stuff that is out there is it, as far as I am concerned. I went on holiday and met with people and organisations. As far as I am concerned, the Foreign Office have known about this. It is not about who else I met; I have friends out there.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Syal|first1=Rajeev|last2=Sherwood|first2=Harriet|title=Priti Patel accuses Foreign Office of briefing against her over Israel meetings|date=3 November 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/nov/03/priti-patel-held-undisclosed-meetings-israel|accessdate=7 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171105071417/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/nov/03/priti-patel-held-undisclosed-meetings-israel|archivedate=5 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/statement-from-international-development-secretary-priti-patel|title=Statement from International Development Secretary Priti Patel \u2013 GOV.UK|publisher=gov.uk|accessdate=9 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109025857/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/statement-from-international-development-secretary-priti-patel|archivedate=9 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nPatel faced calls to resign, with numerous political figures calling her actions a breach of the [[Ministerial Code (United Kingdom)|ministerial code]], which states: \"Ministers must ensure that no conflict arises, or could reasonably be perceived to arise, between their public duties and their private interests, financial or otherwise\".<ref name=\"teletoast\" /> [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] MP [[Jon Trickett]] said, \"She met with the prime minister, and all sorts in Israel, with a lobbyist \u2013 I don't think it is good enough to apologise as I really think this is a serious breach of the ministerial code. The Prime Minister really should be sacking her, or at the very very minimum referring it to the Cabinet Office for investigation\".<ref name=\"teletoast\">{{Cite news |last= Swinford |first= Steven |date= 6 November 2017 |title= Priti Patel should be 'toast' after failing to declare meeting with Israeli Prime Minister, senior Tories say |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/11/06/priti-patel-should-toast-failing-declare-meeting-israeli-prime |work= [[The Daily Telegraph]] |access-date= 6 November 2017 |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20171106234803/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/11/06/priti-patel-should-toast-failing-declare-meeting-israeli-prime/ |archivedate= 6 November 2017 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 6 November, Patel was summoned to meet the Prime Minister [[Theresa May]], who then said that Patel had been \"reminded of her responsibilities\" and announced plans for the ministerial code of conduct to be tightened.<ref>{{cite news |title=PM plans new ministerial code after Priti Patel apology |date=7 November 2017 |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-41896756 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107194711/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-41896756 |archivedate=7 November 2017  }}</ref> Patel released an apology for her actions, and corrected her remarks to ''The Guardian'', which she said gave the false impression that the Foreign Secretary knew about the trip before it happened, and that the only meetings she had had were those then in the public domain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/statement-from-international-development-secretary-priti-patel|title=Statement from International Development Secretary Priti Patel|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref> According to Downing Street, May learned of the meetings when the BBC broke the story on 3 November.<ref>{{cite news|title=Priti Patel resigns from Cabinet over undisclosed meetings with Israeli officials|url=http://www.itv.com/news/2017-11-08/priti-patel/|accessdate=8 November 2017|publisher=ITV News|date=8 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108072812/http://www.itv.com/news/2017-11-08/priti-patel/|archivedate=8 November 2017}}</ref> When May hosted Netanyahu the previous day for the [[Balfour Declaration]] centenary, she was not aware that her minister had had meetings with him in August.\n\nIn the days after Patel's meeting with the Prime Minister and public apology, there were further revelations about her contacts with Israel, including details of two more undisclosed meetings with Israeli officials in Westminster and New York in September 2017,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-41923007|title=Priti Patel quits over Israel meetings row|date=8 November 2017|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> that Patel had not disclosed when she met the Prime Minister on 6th.<ref name=\"FT_2017_11_08\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/c7f278ac-c3c8-11e7-a1d2-6786f39ef675|title=Priti Patel returns to face uproar over Israel trip|last1=Mance|first1=Henry|last2=Pickard|first2=Jim|date=8 November 2017|work=[[Financial Times]]|language=en-GB|access-date=4 August 2019}}</ref> As a result of these further revelations Patel was summoned to Downing Street once more on 8 November, where she met with the Prime Minister and subsequently resigned from her cabinet position, after 16 months in the post.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-41923007|title=Priti Patel quits over Israel meetings row|date=8 November 2017|work=BBC News|accessdate=8 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108194221/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-41923007|archivedate=8 November 2017}}</ref> She was replaced by pro-[[Brexit]] MP [[Penny Mordaunt]] the following day.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/nov/09/penny-mordaunt-replaces-priti-patel-as-international-development-secretary|title=Penny Mordaunt replaces Priti Patel in May's cabinet|work=The Guardian|date=9 November 2017|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109150500/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/nov/09/penny-mordaunt-replaces-priti-patel-as-international-development-secretary|archivedate=9 November 2017}}</ref> Patel claimed that, following her resignation, she was \"overwhelmed with support from colleagues across the political divide\" and from her constituents.<ref>\"[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-essex-41954049 Priti Patel 'overwhelmed' by support after quitting cabinet] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171113084559/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-essex-41954049 |date=13 November 2017 }}\", ''BBC News'', 11 November 2017</ref><ref>\"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/priti-patel-speaks-sacked-international-development-secretary-a8050271.html Priti Patel says she has been 'overwhelmed with support' in first comments since being forced to resign] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171116225208/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/priti-patel-speaks-sacked-international-development-secretary-a8050271.html |date=16 November 2017 }}\" by Rachel Roberts, ''The Independent'', 12 November 2017</ref>\n\n=== Backbencher: 2017\u20132019 ===\n[[File:Rt Hon Priti Patel MP - Tortola, 24 September 2017 (23479788538).jpg|thumb|right|Patel visiting British troops in 2017]]\n\nIn May 2018, Patel questioned the impartiality of the [[Electoral Commission (United Kingdom)|Electoral Commission]] and called for it to investigate [[Britain Stronger in Europe]] or to end its inquiry into the [[Vote Leave]] campaign. Patel expressed concern that Britain Stronger in Europe had been provided with services by other remain campaigns without declaring the expenditure in the appropriate way.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/may/27/priti-patel-calls-investigation-remain-campaign-spending-brexit|title=Priti Patel calls for investigation into remain campaign spending|date=27 May 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In August 2018, the Electoral Commission reported that there was no evidence that Britain Stronger in Europe had breached any laws on campaign spending.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-remain-campaign-spending-priti-patel-electoral-commission-tory-mp-a8474961.html|title=Electoral Commission dismisses Tory MP Priti Patel's claims about Remain campaign spending|date=2 August 2018|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, during the UK's [[Brexit]] negotiations, a government report was leaked which indicated that food supplies and the economy in the [[Republic of Ireland]] could be adversely affected in the event of a no-deal Brexit. Following the report, Patel commented: \"This paper appears to show the government were well aware Ireland will face significant issues in a no-deal scenario. Why hasn't this point been pressed home during negotiations?\" Some sections of the media reported her comments as a suggestion that Britain should exploit Ireland's fear of damage to its economy and food shortages to advance its position with the EU. She was criticised for insensitivity by several other MPs in the light of Britain's part in Ireland's [[Great Famine (Ireland)|Great Famine]] in the 19th century, in which a million people died. Patel said her comments had been taken out of context.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-ireland-food-shortages-threat-risk-priti-patel-negotiate-better-deal-a8672326.html|title=Britain should use risk of food shortages in Ireland to get better Brexit deal, says Priti Patel|date=7 December 2018|work=The Independent|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"irish\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-46488479|title=Irish 'food shortage' comments condemned|date=7 December 2018|work=BBC News}}</ref> Irish EU Commissioner [[Phil Hogan]] said that a food blockade would result in Britain starving, not Ireland, since 43% of food consumed in the UK comes from Ireland.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/dec/07/government-aides-tell-may-they-plan-to-quit-over-her-brexit-deal-mike-wood|title=No 10 hits back as pro-Brexit aides threaten to quit over backstop|last1=Stewart|first1=Heather|date=7 December 2018|work=The Guardian|last2=Syal|first2=Rajeev}}</ref> Journalist [[Eilis O'Hanlon]] criticised the media's characterisation of Patel's comments as a \"manipulative, sinister media-manufactured campaign of character assassination\", further elaborating that the \"divide between fact and comment broke down entirely in response to Priti Patel's comments.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/opinion/comment/eilis-ohanlon-brits-want-to-starve-the-irish-is-the-definition-of-fake-news-37607873.html|title=Eilis O'Hanlon: 'Brits want to starve the Irish' is the definition of fake news'|last=O'Hanlon|first=Eilis|date=9 December 2018|newspaper=[[Irish Independent]]|accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, Patel tweeted supportive messages for [[Turning Point UK]].<ref name=\"guardian-walker\">{{cite news|first1=Peter|last1=Walker|accessdate=4 February 2019|title=Tory MPs back youth group with apparent links to US far right|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/feb/04/tory-mps-back-rightwing-youth-group-turning-point-uk|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=4 February 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\"independent-dearden\">{{cite news|accessdate=2 February 2019|title=Tory MPs voice support for new UK branch of 'sinister' right-wing US group|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/turning-point-uk-jacob-rees-mogg-conservative-right-wing-group-launch-tory-a8762351.html|date=4 February 2019|newspaper=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> In March 2019, Patel backed a pamphlet published by the [[TaxPayers' Alliance]] which called for the international development budget to be reformed, and for the UK alone to decide what constitutes aid, rather than international organisations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/18/priti-patel-joins-calls-for-radical-shake-up-of-aid-budget-rules|title=Priti Patel joins calls for radical shake-up of aid budget rules|last=Wintour|first=Patrick|date=18 March 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n===Home Secretary: 2019\u2013present===\n[[File:PM Johnson and HS Patel at Home Office.jpg|thumb|right|Patel as Home Secretary with Prime Minister Boris Johnson in 2019]]\nPatel was appointed Home Secretary by Boris Johnson in July 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/boris-johnson-goes-to-work-as-prime-minister-nh55w33c0|title=Boris Johnson goes to work as prime minister|first=Elliott|last=Francis|date=24 July 2019|via=thetimes.co.uk}}</ref> Shortly after her appointment, news had transpired that, in May 2019, Patel began working for [[Viasat, Inc.|Viasat]] as a strategic adviser on a salary of \u00a35,000 a month for five hours\u2019 work a month, without seeking prior approval from the government's [[Advisory Committee on Business Appointments]], leading to accusations that she has broken the ministerial code for a second time.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Grierson |first1=Jamie |title=Priti Patel accused of breaching ministerial code for second time |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/26/priti-patel-accused-of-breaching-ministerial-code-for-second-time |work=The Guardian |date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In the December general election, she was re-elected as MP for Witham with an increased majority of 24,082 (48.8%) votes.<ref name=BBC2019/>\n\nIn January 2020, a report by the Youth Empowerment and Innovation Project said that Patel's approach to tackling youth radicalisation was \"madness\" and the Home Office had been \"disengaged\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Townsend |first1=Mark |title=Priti Patel's plan to tackle radicalised youth is so flawed it's mad, says study |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/26/priti-patel-radicalised-youth-plan-so-flawed-its-mad |website=The Guardian |accessdate=26 January 2020 |date=26 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Patel launched a [[Points-based immigration system (United Kingdom)|points-based immigration system]], which will take effect from 1 January 2021.<ref>{{cite press release |url= https://www.gov.uk/government/news/hurricane-irma-foreign-secretarys-visit-to-the-uk-overseas-territories-in-the-Caribbean|title=UK announces new points-based immigration system (dead link)|date=19 February 2020|accessdate=20 February 2020|website=gov.uk}}</ref> The system will aim to reduce the number of immigrants to the UK by requiring visa applicants to meet a set of criteria, such as a salary threshold, ability to speak English, academic qualifications and working in an understaffed industry.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/nri/visa-and-immigration/priti-patel-launches-uks-historic-points-based-visa-system/articleshow/74210378.cms|title=UK Visa: Priti Patel launches UK's 'historic' points-based visa system|work=The Economic Times|date=20 February 2020|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThat same month she came under scrutiny for trying to \"force out\" [[Philip Rutnam|Sir Philip Rutnam]], the most senior civil servant in her department.<ref>{{cite web |title=Priti Patel 'tried to force out top civil servant' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51571619 |website=[[BBC]] |accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Murphy |first1=Joe |title=Priti Patel tried to get rid of top official Sir Philip Rutnam amid 'atmosphere of fear' |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/priti-patel-sir-philip-rutnam-home-office-row-a4367211.html |website=[[Evening Standard]] |accessdate=20 February 2020 |date=20 February 2020}}</ref> Rutnam resigned on 29 February, saying he would be suing the government for [[constructive dismissal]] and that he did not believe Patel's assertion that she had been uninvolved in an alleged campaign briefing against him.<ref>{{cite news |work=BBC News |title=Home Office boss quits over 'campaign against him' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51687287 |date=2020-02-29 |accessdate=2020-02-29}}</ref> Several days later, Patel sent an email to Home Office staff in which she expressed regret at Rutman's decision to resign and thanked him for his service.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-51727632|title=Patel's 'regret' over top adviser's resignation|date=2020-03-03|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-04|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, it was reported that Patel had turned down multiple invitations to appear in front of the [[Home Affairs Select Committee]] to discuss the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus outbreak]]. Patel refused four invitations, since January 2020, to appear before the Committee.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52224203|title=Patel turns down committee appearance four times|date=2020-04-08|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Political ideology and views==\n\nPatel is considered to be on the right-wing of the Conservative Party,<ref name=\"rightwing2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jul/15/priti-patel-tory-rightwinger-promoted-to-treasury|title=Tory rightwinger Priti Patel promoted to Treasury|last=Mason|first=Rowena|date=15 July 2014|work=The Guardian|access-date=10 November 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305001314/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jul/15/priti-patel-tory-rightwinger-promoted-to-treasury|archivedate=5 March 2016}}</ref> with the ''[[Total Politics]]'' website noting that some saw her as a \"modern-day [[Norman Tebbit]]\".<ref name=\"rightwing1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.totalpolitics.com/articles/interview/priti-patel-saviour-tory-right|title=Priti Patel: saviour of the Tory Right|date=5 October 2012|work=TotalPolitics.com|access-date=10 November 2017|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005160644/https://www.totalpolitics.com/articles/interview/priti-patel-saviour-tory-right|archivedate=5 October 2016}}</ref> In ''[[The Guardian]]'', the economics commentator Aditya Chakrabortty characterised her as \"an out-and-out right-winger\" who has no desire to \"claim the centre ground\" in politics.<ref>{{cite news |first=Aditya|last=Chakrabortty |date=23 August 2016 |title=A death foretold: watch as Priti Patel trashes our proud record on aid |website=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/aug/23/priti-patel-foreign-aid-world-poverty |accessdate=20 September 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920145236/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/aug/23/priti-patel-foreign-aid-world-poverty |archivedate=20 September 2016  }}</ref> Patel has cited Thatcher as her political hero,<ref name=totalpolitics/> and has described herself as a \"massive Thatcherite\" (\"I apologise to no one for that\"),<ref>{{Cite journal|journal=[[The House (magazine)|The House]]|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/conservative-party/house/95635/priti-patel-conservative-party-retreating|title=Priti Patel: The Conservative party is retreating from the battle of ideas|first=Sebastian|last=Whale|date=1 June 2018}}</ref> with various news sources characterising her as a [[Thatcherism|Thatcherite]],<ref name=totalpolitics>{{cite news|first=Tom|last=Gockelen-Kozlowski |title=Priti Patel: saviour of the Tory Right |website=Total Politics |date=5 October 2012 |url=https://www.totalpolitics.com/articles/interview/priti-patel-saviour-tory-right |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005160644/https://www.totalpolitics.com/articles/interview/priti-patel-saviour-tory-right |archivedate=5 October 2016  }}</ref><ref name=Warrell/><ref name=week>{{cite news |date=1 March 2016 |title=Priti Patel: the rising star tipped to lead Brexit campaign |work=The Week |url=http://www.theweek.co.uk/brexit/70134/priti-patel-the-rising-star-tipped-to-lead-brexit-campaign |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006165413/http://www.theweek.co.uk/brexit/70134/priti-patel-the-rising-star-tipped-to-lead-brexit-campaign |archivedate=6 October 2016  }}</ref> and while profiling Patel for ''[[The Independent]]'', Tom Peck wrote that she \"could scarcely be more of a Thatcherite\".<ref name=\"thatcherite1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/priti-patel-profile-tory-robot-poised-for-anti-eu-reboot-a6885531.html|title=Priti Patel: Tory 'robot' poised for anti-EU reboot|date=20 February 2016|work=The Independent|access-date=10 November 2017|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107223939/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/priti-patel-profile-tory-robot-poised-for-anti-eu-reboot-a6885531.html|archivedate=7 November 2017}}</ref> She has also previously served as a vice-chair of [[Conservative Friends of Israel]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.cfoi.co.uk/AboutCFI/ |title=About Conservative Friends of Israel |publisher=Conservative Friends of Israel |accessdate=22 September 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809004850/http://www2.cfoi.co.uk/AboutCFI/ |archivedate=9 August 2011  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/priti-patel-the-ambitious-politician-whose-reach-exceeded-her-grasp-1.447636|title=Priti Patel: the ambitious politician whose reach exceeded her grasp|last=Dysch|first=Marcus|date=8 November 2017|accessdate=24 July 2019|work=Jewish Chronicle}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Priti Patel MP.jpg|thumb|left|Patel speaking in 2012]]\n\nShe has taken robust stances on crime, garnering media attention after she argued for the restoration of capital punishment on the BBC's ''[[Question Time (TV series)|Question Time]]'' in September 2011,<ref>{{cite news|last=Helyer |first=Rachel |date=23 September 2011 |title=Furore as Priti Patel urges return of death penalty |url=http://www.theweek.co.uk/people-news/1961/furore-priti-patel-urges-return-death-penalty |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314060951/http://www.theweek.co.uk/people-news/1961/furore-priti-patel-urges-return-death-penalty|archivedate=14 March 2016 |work=The Week|accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Swinford |first=Steven |date=13 May 2015 |title=Priti Patel refuses to say whether she wants to bring back death penalty |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/crime/11601935/Priti-Patel-refuses-to-say-whether-she-wants-to-bring-back-death-penalty.html |archivedate=14 November 2017 |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=11 November 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171114201929/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/crime/11601935/Priti-Patel-refuses-to-say-whether-she-wants-to-bring-back-death-penalty.html  }}</ref> although in 2016 she stated that she no longer held this view.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/patel-backtracks-on-support-for-the-death-penalty-32hw2n76r|title=Patel backtracks on support for the death penalty|first=Michael|last=Savage|date=15 September 2016|work=The Times}}</ref> Patel [[Felony disenfranchisement|opposes prisoner voting]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-politics-12418281/prisoners-voters-john-prescott-and-priti-patel-on-european-law|title=Prisoners' voters: John Prescott and Priti Patel on European law|publisher=BBC News|date=10 February 2011|accessdate=24 September 2019}}</ref> She has also opposed allowing [[Jeremy Bamber]], who was convicted of murder in her constituency, access to media to protest his innocence.<ref>{{cite news|title=Why was killer Bamber given access to media?|date=13 September 2010|work=Maldon Standard|url=http://www.maldonandburnhamstandard.co.uk/news/8388603.Why_was_killer_Bamber_given_access_to_media_/|accessdate=25 February 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140719203944/http://www.maldonandburnhamstandard.co.uk/news/8388603.Why_was_killer_Bamber_given_access_to_media_/|archivedate=19 July 2014}}</ref> Patel voted against the [[Marriage (Same Sex Couples) Act 2013|2013 Marriage (Same Sex Couples) Bill]], which introduced same-sex marriage in England and Wales.<ref>{{cite web|title=MP-by-MP: Gay marriage vote|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-21346694|website=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nPatel has been criticised by some for raising issues in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] related to her time working for the tobacco and alcohol industries.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |last=Doward |first=Jamie |date=3 May 2014 |title=Tory cigarette packaging rebel Priti Patel is ex-tobacco lobbyist |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/may/03/tory-cigarette-packaging-rebel-tobacco-lobbyist |website=The Guardian |accessdate=31 May 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150315031159/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/may/03/tory-cigarette-packaging-rebel-tobacco-lobbyist |archivedate=15 March 2015  }}</ref> As a parliamentarian, Patel has been consistently supportive of tobacco industry viewpoints: in October 2010, she voted for the smoking ban to be overturned; in December 2010, she signed a letter requesting that plain packaging for cigarettes be reconsidered. Patel has also campaigned with the drinks industry, holding a reception in parliament for the ''Call Time On Duty Campaign'' in favour of ending the alcohol duty escalator supported by the Wine and Spirit Trade Association, the Scotch Whisky Association and the [[TaxPayers' Alliance]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wsta.co.uk/press/697-call-time-on-duty-campaign-makes-its-case-to-parliamentarians |title=Call Time on Duty campaign makes its case to Parliamentarians |publisher=Wsta.co.uk |accessdate=30 May 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530054552/http://wsta.co.uk/press/697-call-time-on-duty-campaign-makes-its-case-to-parliamentarians |archivedate=30 May 2015  }}</ref>\n\nSpeaking on [[BBC Radio Kent]] in March 2018, Patel said that she found the commonly-used abbreviation ''BME'' (for [[Classification of ethnicity in the United Kingdom|Black and Minority Ethnic]]) to be \"patronisin' and insultin'\". This was because being born in Britain, she considered herself British first and foremost.<ref name=BME/>\n\n==Personal life==\nPatel has been married to Alex Sawyer since 2004.<ref>{{cite book|first=Lucy|last=Hume|title=People of Today 2017|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oAM7DwAAQBAJ&pg=RA1-PA1817|date=5 October 2017|publisher=Debrett's|isbn=978-1-9997670-3-7|page=1817|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180204164306/https://books.google.com/books?id=oAM7DwAAQBAJ&pg=RA1-PA1817|archivedate=4 February 2018}}</ref> Sawyer is a [[marketing consultant]] for the stock exchange [[NASDAQ]]. He is also a Conservative [[councillor]] and Cabinet Member for Communities on the council of the [[London Borough of Bexley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://democracy.bexley.gov.uk/mgUserInfo.aspx?UID=177|title=Councillor Alex Sawyer|accessdate=24 September 2019|publisher=Bexley Borough Council}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://directory.londoncouncils.gov.uk/directory/bexley/executive/|title=London Borough of Bexley|publisher=London Councils|accessdate=9 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110225244/http://directory.londoncouncils.gov.uk/directory/bexley/executive/|archivedate=10 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=Kenber/> Sawyer also worked part-time as her office manager from February 2014 to August 2017.<ref name=Kenber>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/priti-patels-husband-comes-off-the-payroll-brhr75j95|title=Priti Patel's husband comes off the payroll|work=The Times|date=8 August 2017|last=Kenber|first=Billy}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/11706561/One-in-four-MPs-employs-a-family-member-the-full-list-revealed.html|title=One in five MPs employs a family member: the full list revealed|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=29 June 2015|last=Hope|first=Christopher|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170402065627/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/11706561/One-in-four-MPs-employs-a-family-member-the-full-list-revealed.html|archivedate=2 April 2017}}</ref> Together they have a son born in August 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisistotalessex.co.uk/news/Newborn-Freddie-Tory-party-s-youngest-member/article-268112-detail/article.html |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130505130100/http://www.thisistotalessex.co.uk/news/Newborn-Freddie-Tory-party-s-youngest-member/article-268112-detail/article.html |url-status=dead |archivedate=5 May 2013 |title=Newborn Freddie is the Tory party's youngest member |work=This is Total Essex |date=14 August 2008 |accessdate=22 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Priti Patel}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.priti4witham.com/}}\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = priti-patel/4066 | hansard = | hansardcurr = <!-- 5618 --> | guardian = 9319/priti-patel | publicwhip = Priti_Patel | theywork = priti_patel | bbc = 37703.stm | journalisted = }}\n*{{C-SPAN}}\n* [http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b09drhhk 2017 Profile of Patel] on [[BBC Radio Four]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br />for [[Witham (UK Parliament constituency)|Witham]]|years=[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Gauke]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Exchequer Secretary to the Treasury]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Damian Hinds]]|rows=2}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Esther McVey]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department for Work and Pensions|Minister of State for Employment]]|years=2015\u20132016}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Justine Greening]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for International Development]]|years=2016\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Penny Mordaunt]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sajid Javid]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Home Secretary]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Great Offices of State}}\n{{Cabinet of David Cameron}}\n{{Second Cameron Cabinet}}\n{{First May Cabinet}}\n{{Second May Cabinet}}\n{{Johnson Cabinet}}\n{{Home Secretaries}}\n{{G8-Interior}}\n{{Secretary of State for International Development}}\n{{East of England Conservative Party MPs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patel, Priti}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Keele University]]\n[[Category:English people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Essex]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Critics of the European Union]]\n[[Category:British politicians of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Gujarati descent]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Cabinet of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Watford Grammar School for Girls]]\n[[Category:People from Harrow, London]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of State for the Home Department]]\n[[Category:Recipients of Pravasi Bharatiya Samman]]\n[[Category:Female interior ministers]]\n[[Category:Female critics of feminism]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Priti Patel\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Rt Hon Priti Patel MP crop 2.jpg\n| office = [[Home Secretary]]\n| primeminister = [[Boris Johnson]]\n| term_start = 24 July 2019\n| predecessor = [[Sajid Javid]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = [[Secretary of State for International Development]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start1 = 14 July 2016\n| term_end1 = 8 November 2017\n| predecessor1 = [[Justine Greening]]\n| successor1 = [[Penny Mordaunt]]\n| office2 = [[Department for Work and Pensions|Minister of State for Employment]]\n| primeminister2 = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start2 = 11 May 2015\n| term_end2 = 14 July 2016\n| predecessor2 = [[Esther McVey]]\n| successor2 = [[Damian Hinds]]\n| office3 = [[Exchequer Secretary to the Treasury]]\n| primeminister3 = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start3 = 15 July 2014\n| term_end3 = 11 May 2015\n| predecessor3 = [[David Gauke]]\n| successor3 = [[Damian Hinds]]\n| office4 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br> for [[Witham (UK Parliament constituency)|Witham]]\n| term_start4 = 6 May 2010\n| term_end4 = \n| predecessor4 = Constituency established\n| successor4 =\n| majority4 = 24,082 (48.8%)<ref name=BBC2019>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14001045|title=Witham|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=20 September 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_name = Priti Sushil Patel\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1972|3|29}}\n| birth_place = [[London]],  England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| signature = \n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] (before 1995; since 1997)\n| otherparty = [[Referendum Party|Referendum]] (1995\u20131997)\n| spouse = {{marriage|Alex Sawyer|2004}}\n| children = 1\n| alma_mater = [[Keele University]]<br />[[University of Essex]]\n| caption = Patel in 2020\n}}\n'''Priti Sushil Patel'''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201516/cmhansrd/cm150519/debtext/150519-0001.htm |title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 19 May 2015 (pt 0001) |publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom |date=19 May 2015 |accessdate=4 July 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404092037/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201516/cmhansrd/cm150519/debtext/150519-0001.htm |archivedate=4 April 2016}}</ref> (born 29 March 1972) is a British politician who has served as [[Secretary of State for the Home Department]] since 2019 and the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Witham (UK Parliament constituency)|Witham]] since [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]. She served as [[Secretary of State for International Development]] from 2016 to 2017. A member of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]], she is ideologically positioned on the party's right wing and considers herself to be a [[Thatcherism|Thatcherite]].\n\nPatel was born in London to a [[Indians in Uganda|Ugandan-Indian]] family. She was educated at [[Keele University]] and the [[University of Essex]]. Inspired to get involved in politics by Conservative Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]], she was initially involved with the [[Referendum Party]] before switching allegiance to the Conservatives. She worked for the public-relations consultancy firm [[Weber Shandwick]] for several years, as part of which she lobbied for the tobacco and alcohol industries. Intending to switch to a political career, she unsuccessfully contested [[Nottingham North (UK Parliament constituency)|Nottingham North]] at the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]]. After [[David Cameron]] became [[party leader|Conservative leader]], he recommended Patel for the party's \"[[Conservative A-List|A-List]]\" of [[prospective parliamentary candidate|prospective candidates]]. She was first elected MP for Witham, a Conservative [[safe seat]] in [[Essex]], at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], before being re-elected in [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]], [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]] and [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]. Under Cameron's government, Patel was appointed [[Department of Work and Pensions|Minister of State for Employment]] and served as vice-chair of the [[Conservative Friends of Israel]]. She attracted attention for her [[social conservatism|socially conservative]] stances.\n\nA longstanding [[Euroscepticism|Eurosceptic]], Patel was a leading figure in the [[Vote Leave]] campaign during the build-up to the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum on UK membership]] of the [[European Union]]. Following Cameron's resignation, Patel backed [[Theresa May]] as Conservative leader; May subsequently appointed Patel [[Secretary of State for International Development]]. In 2017 she was involved in a political scandal involving unauthorised meetings with the [[Government of Israel]], ending her tenure as International Development Secretary. Under [[Boris Johnson]]'s premiership, she became Home Secretary in 2019, the first ethnic minority woman to hold the office.\n\nPatel has been criticised by political opponents for defending the tobacco and alcohol industries,<ref name=\":3\" /> and for advocating threatening the [[Republic of Ireland]] with food shortages during Brexit negotiations.<ref name=\"food\">{{cite news |last1=Kentish |first1=Benjamin |title=Britain should use risk of economic damage Ireland to get better Brexit deal, suggests Priti Patel |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-ireland-food-shortages-threat-risk-priti-patel-negotiate-better-deal-a8672326.html |work=The Independent |date=7 December 2018 |language=en |quote=Ms Patel said her comments had been taken out of context and that she had not referred specifically to the risk of food shortages. Rather, she said, she had been arguing that \"the consequences of not getting a favourable deal for all should help to focus minds\".}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Learmonth |first1=Andrew |title=Fury at Tory's plan to use food shortages as leverage in Brexit talks |url=https://www.thenational.scot/news/17284900.priti-patel-suggests-using-food-shortage-threat-in-brexit-talks/ |work=[[The National (Scotland)|The National]] |date=8 December 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Patel said her comments were \"taken out of context\" and that she did not refer specifically to the risk of food shortages.<ref name=\"food\"/><ref name=\"irish\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-46488479|title=Irish 'food shortage' comments condemned|date=7 December 2018|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nPriti Patel was born on 29 March 1972 to Sushil and Anjana Patel in London.<ref name=BME>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-43350527|title=BME label insulting, says ex-minister Priti Patel|work=BBC News|date=9 March 2018|accessdate=10 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/nov/08/priti-patel-an-outspoken-brexiter-who-went-too-quietly-to-israel|title=Priti Patel: an outspoken Brexiter who went too quietly to Israel|first=Anushka|last=Asthana|date=8 November 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=13 November 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171113054003/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/nov/08/priti-patel-an-outspoken-brexiter-who-went-too-quietly-to-israel|archivedate=13 November 2017}}</ref> Her paternal grandparents were born in [[Tarapur, Gujarat]], before emigrating to [[Uganda]], and establishing a shop in [[Kampala]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/explained/who-is-priti-patel-britains-new-home-secretary-5852090/|title=Explained: Who's Priti Patel, Britain's new Home Secretary?|date=28 July 2019|work=The Indian Express}}</ref> In the 1960s her parents emigrated to the UK and settled in [[Hertfordshire, England|Hertfordshire]].<ref name=ibtnew>{{cite news |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/priti-patel-mp-new-face-britains-conservative-party-1000142 |title=Priti Patel, MP: The New Face Of Britain's Conservative Party |work=International Business Times |date=8 January 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530164139/http://www.ibtimes.com/priti-patel-mp-new-face-britains-conservative-party-1000142 |archivedate=30 May 2015  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.eadt.co.uk/news/east-meets-westminster-young-asian-and-female-essex-mp-priti-patel-is-modern-face-of-the-tories-1-1447039|work=Eastern Anglia Daily Times|date=16 July 2012|accessdate=10 February 2020|title=East meets Westminster: Young, Asian and female - Essex MP Priti Patel is modern face of the Tories}}</ref> They established a chain of [[Newsagent's shop|newsagents]] in London and the [[South East of England]].<ref name=totalpolitics/><ref name=Warrell>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/52fbc7c8-b50d-11e9-8cb2-799a3a8cf37b|title=How radical will Priti Patel be at the UK Home Office?|work=Financial Times|last1=Warrell|first1=Helen|last2=Staton|first2=Bethan|date=4 August 2019}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nPatel attended [[Watford Grammar School for Girls]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Hope|first=Christopher |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/10969676/Pen-portraits-of-the-10-Conservative-women-ministers-who-were-promoted-in-the-reshuffle.html|title=Pen portraits of the 10 Conservative women ministers who were promoted in the reshuffle|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=15 July 2014|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517122250/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/10969676/Pen-portraits-of-the-10-Conservative-women-ministers-who-were-promoted-in-the-reshuffle.html|archivedate=17 May 2017}}</ref> before studying Economics at [[Keele University]] and then pursuing postgraduate studies in British Government and Politics at the [[University of Essex]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-28292058 |title=The Conservative women on the rise in Cameron's reshuffle |work=[[BBC News]] |date=15 July 2014 |accessdate=30 May 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150903230217/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-28292058 |archivedate=3 September 2015  }}</ref><ref name=profile>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-41913203|title=Profile: Priti Patel|date=8 November 2017 |publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109081403/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-41913203 |archivedate=9 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Conservative Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]] became her political heroine: according to Patel, she \"had a unique ability to understand what made people tick, households tick and businesses tick. Managing the economy, balancing the books and making decisions \u2013 not purchasing things the country couldn't afford\".<ref name=totalpolitics/> She first joined the Conservative Party as a teenager, when [[John Major]] was [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]].<ref name=ibtnew />\n\n==Early career==\nAfter graduating, Patel became an intern at Conservative Central Office (now known as [[Conservative Campaign Headquarters]]), having been selected by [[Andrew Lansley]] (then Head of the [[Conservative Research Department]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/home-affairs/house/71738/priti-please|title=Priti, please|last=Waugh|first=Paul|date=30 January 2014|accessdate=14 September 2019|publisher=Politics Home}}</ref> From 1995 to 1997, Patel headed the press office of the [[Referendum Party]], a single-issue Eurosceptic party.<ref name=profile/>\n\nIn 1997, Patel left to join the Conservative Party having been offered a post to work for the new leader [[William Hague]] in his press office, dealing with media relations in London and the [[South East of England]].<ref name = \"QT2007 summary\">{{cite news | title = This week's panel | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/6443391.stm | date = 15 March 2007 | work = Question Time | publisher = BBC | accessdate = 31 May 2015 }}</ref> In August 2003, the ''[[Financial Times]]'' published an article citing quotes from Patel and alleging that \"[[Racism|racist]] attitudes\" persisted in the Conservative Party, and that \"there's a lot of bigotry around\".<ref name=\"BBC A-List\">{{cite news|last=Brant |first=Robin |date=4 December 2006 |title=A year on, has the A-list worked? |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6206132.stm |publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=31 May 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808102841/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6206132.stm |archivedate=8 August 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Patel wrote to the ''FT'' countering its article stating that her comments had been misinterpreted to imply that she had been blocked as a [[prospective parliamentary candidate|party candidate]] because of her [[ethnicity]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/question_time/6443391.stm|title=This week's panel|date=15 March 2007|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000 Patel left the employment of the Conservative Party to work for [[Weber Shandwick]], a [[public relations|PR]] consulting firm.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prweek.com/channel/PublicAffairs/article/1002450/many-lobbyists-win-seats-majority-decreased |title=Many lobbyists win seats but some see majority decreased|first=David|last=Singleton|work=PR Week |date=11 May 2010 |accessdate=22 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807140140/http://www.prweek.com/channel/PublicAffairs/article/1002450/many-lobbyists-win-seats-majority-decreased |archivedate=7 August 2011}}</ref> According to an investigative article published by ''[[The Guardian]]'' in May 2015, Patel was one of seven Weber Shandwick employees who worked on [[British American Tobacco]] (BAT) \u2013 a major account. The team had been tasked with helping BAT manage the company's public image during the controversy around the Burma factory being used as source of funds by its military dictatorship and poor payment to factory workers. The crisis eventually ended with BAT pulling out of Burma in 2003. The article went on to quote BAT employees who felt that though a majority of Weber Shandwick employees were uncomfortable working with them, Patel's group was fairly relaxed. The article also quoted internal documents specifying that a part of Patel's job was also to lobby [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]]s against EU tobacco regulations. She worked for Weber Shandwick for three years.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jamie|last=Doward |date=30 May 2015 |title=Minister worked as spin doctor for tobacco giant that paid workers \u00a315 a month |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/may/30/priti-patel-worked-as-spin-doctor-tobacco-firm-burma-scandal |work=The Guardian |accessdate=30 May 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530154927/http://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/may/30/priti-patel-worked-as-spin-doctor-tobacco-firm-burma-scandal |archivedate=30 May 2015  }}</ref>\n\nPatel then moved to the British multinational alcoholic beverages company, [[Diageo]], and worked in [[Corporate communication|corporate relations]] between 2003 and 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.prweek.com/article/771926/tory-rising-star-snared-ws|title=Tory rising star is snared by WS|date=6 December 2007|access-date=10 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110172111/https://www.prweek.com/article/771926/tory-rising-star-snared-ws|archivedate=10 November 2017|work=PR Week}}</ref> In 2007, she rejoined Weber Shandwick as Director of Corporate and Public Affairs practices. According to their press release, during her time at Diageo, Patel had \"worked on international public policy issues related to the wider impact of alcohol in society.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Tory rising star returns to Weber Shandwick|url=http://www.webershandwick.co.uk/homepage-sections/what-we-are-up-to/157|publisher=Weber Shandwick|accessdate=30 May 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080116141016/http://www.webershandwick.co.uk/homepage-sections/what-we-are-up-to/157|archivedate=16 January 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\n\n===Member of Parliament for Witham: 2010\u2013present===\n[[File:Panel for 'Britannia Unchained' (8077416892).jpg|thumb|right|Patel on the panel of \"Britannia Unchained\"]]\n\nIn the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]], she stood as the Conservative candidate for [[Nottingham North (UK Parliament constituency)|Nottingham North]], losing to the incumbent [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] MP [[Graham Allen (politician)|Graham Allen]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Natalie|last=Fahy|url=http://www.nottinghampost.com/Election-results-Nottingham-North-2001-2005-2010/story-26449521-detail/story.html|title=Election results for Nottingham North from 2001, 2005 and 2010 |work=Nottingham Post|date=6 May 2015 |accessdate=4 July 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706182532/http://www.nottinghampost.com/Election-results-Nottingham-North-2001-2005-2010/story-26449521-detail/story.html |archivedate=6 July 2015  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/vote2005/html/439.stm|title=Result: Nottingham North |publisher=BBC News|accessdate=14 September 2019|date=6 May 2005}}</ref> Despite her unsuccessful parliamentary campaign, Patel was identified as a promising candidate by new party leader David Cameron, and was offered a place on the \"[[Conservative A-List|A-List]]\" of Conservative [[prospective parliamentary candidate]]s (PPC).<ref name = \"BBC A-List\"/> In November 2006, she was adopted as the PPC for the notionally safe Conservative seat of [[Witham (UK Parliament constituency)|Witham]] \u2014 a new constituency in central Essex created after a [[Boundary Commissions (United Kingdom)|boundary review]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/ |title=Priti Patel takes Witham by storm |work=East Anglian Daily Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051210052439/http://www.eadt.co.uk/ |archivedate=10 December 2005 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Priti Patel takes Witham by storm|first=Graham|last=Dines|date=21 November 2006|work=Eastern Daily Press|url=http://www.edp24.co.uk/news/politics/priti_patel_takes_witham_by_storm_1_78129|accessdate=12 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130509232612/http://www.edp24.co.uk/news/politics/priti_patel_takes_witham_by_storm_1_78129|archivedate=9 May 2013}}</ref> \u2014 before gaining a majority of 15,196 at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]]. She was drafted into the [[Number 10 Policy Unit]] in October 2013,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/coffeehouse/2013/10/new-number-10-policy-board-announced/|title=New Number 10 policy board announced|work=The Spectator|date=15 October 2013|accessdate=15 July 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140105195313/http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/coffeehouse/2013/10/new-number-10-policy-board-announced/|archivedate=5 January 2014}}</ref> and was promoted as [[Exchequer Secretary to the Treasury]] the following summer.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/priti-patel-cabinet-home-secretary-boris-views-beliefs-israel-ireland-death-penalty-a9018616.html|work=The Independent|title=Priti Patel: Disgraced former minister who previously supported death penalty named home secretary by Boris Johnson|date=24 July 2019|accessdate=10 February 2020|last=Cockburn|first=Harry}}</ref>\n\nAlong with fellow Conservative MPs [[Kwasi Kwarteng]], [[Dominic Raab]], [[Chris Skidmore]] and [[Liz Truss]], Patel was considered one of the \"Class of 2010\" who represented the party's \"new Right\".<ref name=week/> Together they co-authored ''[[Britannia Unchained]]'', a book published in 2012. This work was critical of levels of workplace productivity in the UK, making the controversial statement that \"once they enter the workplace, the British are among the worst idlers in the world\". The authors suggested that to change this situation, the UK should reduce the size of the [[welfare state]] and seek to emulate the working conditions in countries like Singapore, Hong Kong, and South Korea rather than those of other European nations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/tackle-lazy-britain-fellow-tories-tell-david-cameron-8056787.html|title=Tackle 'lazy' Britain, fellow Tories tell David Cameron|website=London Evening Standard|date=17 August 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161207135125/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/tackle-lazy-britain-fellow-tories-tell-david-cameron-8056787.html|archivedate=7 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Randeep|last=Ramesh|date=17 August 2012 |title=Tory young bloods say Britons are idlers who need to emulate Asia |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/aug/17/tory-backbenchers-urge-welfare-reforms |work=The Guardian |accessdate=31 May 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312145055/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/aug/17/tory-backbenchers-urge-welfare-reforms |archivedate=12 March 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref> In the same year, Patel was elected on to the executive of the [[1922 Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-18093877|website=BBC News|date=17 May 2012|accessdate=22 September 2019|title=New faces elected on to influential Conservative 1922 committee}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, Patel criticised the plan of the [[Academies Enterprise Trust]] to merge the New Rickstones and Maltings Academies, claiming that to do so would be detrimental to school standards.<ref>{{cite news|first=Will|last=Lodge|title=Witham: MP Priti Patel voices opposition to merger of Maltings and New Rickstones Academies |website=East Anglian Daily News |date=15 October 2014 |url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/witham_mp_priti_patel_voices_opposition_to_merger_of_maltings_and_new_rickstones_academies_1_3807267 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150810073826/http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/witham_mp_priti_patel_voices_opposition_to_merger_of_maltings_and_new_rickstones_academies_1_3807267 |archivedate=10 August 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Patel lodged a complaint with the [[BBC]] alleging one-sided coverage critical of [[Narendra Modi]] on the eve of [[Prime Minister of India|his]] victory in [[2014 Indian general elections|2014 Indian elections]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/nri/Indian-origin-MP-takes-BBCs-Modi-coverage-complaint-to-UK-ministry/articleshow/37035502.cms|title=Indian-origin MP takes BBC's 'Modi coverage' complaint to UK ministry|work=The Times of India|date=22 June 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140622194325/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/nri/Indian-origin-MP-takes-BBCs-Modi-coverage-complaint-to-UK-ministry/articleshow/37035502.cms|archivedate=22 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/cameron-aide-takes-on-bbc-over-modi-india-image/article1-1231733.aspx|title=British PM Cameron's aide takes on BBC over critical comments against Modi|work=Hindustan Times|date=20 June 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140623061057/http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/cameron-aide-takes-on-bbc-over-modi-india-image/article1-1231733.aspx|archivedate=23 June 2014}}</ref> In January 2015, Patel was presented with a \"Jewels of Gujarat\" award in [[Ahmedabad]], India, and in the city she gave a keynote speech at the Gujarat Chamber of Commerce.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/world-location-news/uk-minister-priti-patel-honoured-at-jewels-of-gujarat-reception|title=UK Minister Priti Patel honoured at 'Jewels of Gujarat' reception|publisher=British High Commission, New Delhi|date=7 January 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402122240/https://www.gov.uk/government/world-location-news/uk-minister-priti-patel-honoured-at-jewels-of-gujarat-reception|archivedate=2 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|general election of May 2015]] \u2014 a Conservative victory \u2014 Patel retained her parliamentary seat with 27,123 votes, increasing her majority by 4,358.<ref>{{cite news|first=Will|last=Lodge |title=Election 2015: Priti Patel extends majority for Conservatives in Witham |date=8 May 2015 |website=East Anglian Daily Times |url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/election_2015_priti_patel_extends_majority_for_conservatives_in_witham_1_4065630 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150718234906/http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/election_2015_priti_patel_extends_majority_for_conservatives_in_witham_1_4065630 |archivedate=18 July 2015  }}</ref> During the campaign, she had criticised [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] rival John Clarke for referring to her as a \"sexy [[Bond villain]]\" and a \"[[village idiot]]\" on [[social media]]; he apologised.<ref>{{cite news|first=Annabelle|last=Dickson |date=24 March 2015 |website=East Anglian Daily Times |title=Tories want Labour election candidate who described Witham MP Priti Patel as 'sexy Bond villain' to be axed |url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/tories_want_labour_election_candidate_who_described_witham_mp_priti_patel_as_sexy_bond_villain_to_be_axed_1_4006347 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150328060608/http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/tories_want_labour_election_candidate_who_described_witham_mp_priti_patel_as_sexy_bond_villain_to_be_axed_1_4006347 |archivedate=28 March 2015  }}</ref> After the election, Patel rose to Cabinet-level as [[Minister of State|Minister of State for Employment]] in the [[Department for Work and Pensions]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2015-05-11/priti-patel-appointed-as-employment-minister/|title=Priti Patel appointed as Employment Minister|publisher=ITV News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150514021143/http://www.itv.com/news/update/2015-05-11/priti-patel-appointed-as-employment-minister/|archivedate=14 May 2015}}</ref> and was sworn of the [[Privy Council]] on 14 May 2015. \n\nIn October 2015 a junior employee at the [[Department for Work and Pensions]] was dismissed from her role. In response, the employee brought a formal complaint of bullying and harassment against the department, including Patel. In 2017 a settlement was reached for \u00a325,000 after the member of staff threatened to bring a legal claim of bullying, harassment and discrimination on the grounds of race and disability against the department and Patel.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Titheradge|first=Rianna Croxford and Noel|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51705069|title=Patel aide got \u00a325k payout 'over bullying'|date=2020-03-03|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-03|language=en-GB}}</ref>  \n\nIn December 2015, Patel voted to support Cameron's planned bombing of [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] targets in Syria.<ref>{{cite news|first=Annabelle|last=Dickson |title=Prime Minister given backing to extend air strikes to Syria |date=2 December 2015 |website=East Anglian Daily Times |url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/prime_minister_given_backing_to_extend_air_strikes_to_syria_how_did_your_mp_vote_1_4334448 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151203215002/http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/prime_minister_given_backing_to_extend_air_strikes_to_syria_how_did_your_mp_vote_1_4334448 |archivedate=3 December 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n===Brexit campaign: 2015\u20132016===\nFollowing Cameron's announcement of [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|a referendum on the UK's continuing membership]] of the [[European Union]] (EU), Patel was widely touted as a likely \"poster girl\" for the [[Vote Leave]] campaign.<ref name=\"ibtimes_iansilvera\">{{cite news|first=Ian|last=Silvera|title=Priti Patel: Who is the top Tory right-winger tipped to be the face of the Brexit campaign? |date=8 February 2016 |website=International Business Times |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/priti-patel-who-top-tory-right-winger-tipped-be-face-brexit-campaign-1542619 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160209093440/http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/priti-patel-who-top-tory-right-winger-tipped-be-face-brexit-campaign-1542619 |archivedate=9 February 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Patel said that the EU is \"undemocratic and interferes too much in our daily lives\". She publicly stated that immigration from elsewhere in the EU was overstretching the resources of UK schools.<ref>{{cite news |first=Rowena|last=Mason|title=Priti Patel warns of EU migration threat to UK class sizes |work=The Guardian |date=21 June 2016 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/21/priti-patel-warns-of-eu-migration-threat-to-uk-class-sizes |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011022319/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/21/priti-patel-warns-of-eu-migration-threat-to-uk-class-sizes |archivedate=11 October 2016  }}</ref> She helped to launch the Women For Britain campaign for anti-EU women; at their launch party, she compared their campaign with that of [[Emmeline Pankhurst]] and the [[Suffragettes]], for which she was criticised by Emmeline's great-granddaughter Helen Pankhurst.<ref>{{cite news |first=Annabelle|last=Dickson|work=East Anglian Daily Times |date=8 March 2016 |title=Essex MP under fire for likening women who campaign to leave the European Union to the suffragettes |url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/essex_mp_under_fire_for_likening_women_who_campaign_to_leave_the_european_union_to_the_suffragettes_1_4447801 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006143717/http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/essex_mp_under_fire_for_likening_women_who_campaign_to_leave_the_european_union_to_the_suffragettes_1_4447801 |archivedate=6 October 2016  }}</ref>\n\nFollowing the success of the \"[[Brexit|Leave]]\" vote in the EU referendum, Cameron resigned, resulting in a leadership contest within the party. Patel openly supported [[Theresa May]] as his successor, claiming that she had the \"strength and experience\" for the job, while arguing that May's main challenger [[Andrea Leadsom]] would prove too divisive to win a general election.<ref>{{cite news|title=Priti Patel: Andrea Leadsom could become a Tory Corbyn |first=Tim|last=Ross |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=9 July 2016 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/09/priti-patel-interview-andrea-leadsom-could-become-a-tory-corbyn/ |archivedate=9 July 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160709222928/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/09/priti-patel-interview-andrea-leadsom-could-become-a-tory-corbyn/  }}</ref> In November 2017, Patel was critical of the UK government [[Brexit negotiations]] and stated: \"I would have told the EU in particular to sod off with their excessive financial demands\".<ref>{{cite news|date=27 November 2017|title=I would have told the EU to sod off over Brexit divorce bill, Priti Patel says|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/11/27/would-have-told-eu-sod-brexit-divorce-bill-priti-patel-says/|archivedate=2 December 2017|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=2 December 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202042938/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/11/27/would-have-told-eu-sod-brexit-divorce-bill-priti-patel-says/}}</ref>\n\n===Secretary of State for International Development: 2016\u20132017===\n\n[[File:Narendra Modi is greeted by British MP Priti Patel after arriving at Heathrow Airport.jpg|thumb|Patel greeting Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] at [[Heathrow Airport]] on 12 November 2015|alt=]]\n\nAfter becoming Prime Minister, in July 2016 May appointed Patel to the position of International Development Secretary. Patel described herself as being \"delighted\" with the post despite a statement made in 2013 suggesting that the Department for International Development (DFID) should be scrapped and replaced with a Department for International Trade and Development.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/new-international-development-secretary-priti-patel-called-for-department-for-international-a7137331.html |title=The new International Development Secretary wanted to scrap what is now her department |website=The Independent|date=14 July 2016|first=Jon|last=Stone|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628034520/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/new-international-development-secretary-priti-patel-called-for-department-for-international-a7137331.html |archivedate=28 June 2017}}</ref>\nMany staff at the department were concerned about Patel's appointment, both because of her support for Brexit and because of her longstanding scepticism regarding international development and aid spending.<ref>{{cite news |title=Dfid officials are worried about Priti Patel, but it's Brexit they should be frightened of |date=20 September 2016 |first=Stephen|last=Bush|website=New Statesman |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/staggers/2016/09/dfid-officials-are-worried-about-priti-patel-its-brexit-they-should-be |accessdate=20 September 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920154716/http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/staggers/2016/09/dfid-officials-are-worried-about-priti-patel-its-brexit-they-should-be |archivedate=20 September 2016  }}</ref>\n\nOn taking the position, Patel stated that too much UK aid was wasted or spent inappropriately, declaring that she would adopt an approach rooted in \"core Conservative principles\" and emphasise international development through trade as opposed to aid.<ref>{{cite news |first=Ben|last=Quinn|title=Priti Patel plans foreign aid overhaul based on 'core Tory values' |website=The Guardian |date=14 September 2016 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/sep/14/priti-patel-plans-foreign-aid-overhaul-based-on-core-tory-values |accessdate=20 September 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920081621/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/sep/14/priti-patel-plans-foreign-aid-overhaul-based-on-core-tory-values |archivedate=20 September 2016  }}</ref> In September, Patel announced that the UK would contribute \u00a31.1&nbsp;billion to a global aid fund used to combat [[malaria]], [[tuberculosis]], and [[HIV/AIDS]], but added that any further aid deals would include \"performance agreements\" meaning that the British Government could reduce aid by 10% if specific criteria were not met by the recipient country.<ref>{{cite news|first=Peter|last=Dominiczak|title=Britain will withhold foreign aid money if performance countries' targets are not met  |date=18 September 2016 |work=The Daily Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/09/18/foreign-aid-money-to-be-limited-if-performance-targets-are-not-m/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919130230/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/09/18/foreign-aid-money-to-be-limited-if-performance-targets-are-not-m/ |archivedate=19 September 2016 }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016 she expressed opposition to the construction of 28 [[affordable housing|affordable home]]s at the Lakelands development in [[Stanway, Essex|Stanway]], referring to it as an \"unacceptable loss of open space\" and criticising [[Colchester Borough Council]] for permitting it.<ref>{{cite web|first=Matt|last=Stott|title=Witham MP Priti Patel labels Colchester Borough Council 'rotten' in Stanway housing development dispute |date=6 September 2016 |website=East Anglian Daily Times |url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/witham_mp_priti_patel_labels_colchester_borough_council_rotten_in_stanway_housing_development_dispute_1_4685526 |accessdate=20 September 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160906092140/http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/witham_mp_priti_patel_labels_colchester_borough_council_rotten_in_stanway_housing_development_dispute_1_4685526 |archivedate=6 September 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> That same month, the council's chief executive Adrian Pritchard issued a complaint against Patel, claiming that she had acted \"inappropriately\" in urging [[Sajid Javid]] to approve the construction of an out-of-town [[retail park]] after it had already been rejected by Colchester Council.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ryan|last=Jennings|title=Council claims MP acted 'inappropriately' in Tollgate planning row|work=The Daily Gazette|date=20 September 2016|url=http://www.gazette-news.co.uk/news/14752217.Council_claims_MP_acted__inappropriately__in_Tollgate_planning_row/|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921195321/http://www.gazette-news.co.uk/news/14752217.Council_claims_MP_acted__inappropriately__in_Tollgate_planning_row/|archivedate=21 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:The Secretary of State for International Development, United Kingdom, Ms. Priti Patel calling on the Prime Minister, Shri Narendra Modi, in New Delhi on August 13, 2016.jpg|thumb|left|Patel with Modi in 2016]]\n\nAlso in September, proposals were put forward for a change to the boundaries of parliamentary constituencies across the UK. As a result of the plans, Patel's seat of Witham would be merged with neighbouring [[Maldon (UK Parliament constituency)|Maldon]]. This would potentially require her to compete against Maldon MP [[John Whittingdale]] for the new seat of Witham and Maldon.<ref>{{cite news|first=Matt|last=Stott|title=Witham MP Priti Patel and Maldon MP John Whittingdale set to fight over merged seat at 2020 General Election |date=13 September 2016 |website=East Anglian Daily Times |url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/witham_mp_priti_patel_and_maldon_mp_john_whittingdale_set_to_fight_over_merged_seat_at_2020_general_election_1_4693809 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917004223/http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/witham_mp_priti_patel_and_maldon_mp_john_whittingdale_set_to_fight_over_merged_seat_at_2020_general_election_1_4693809 |archivedate=17 September 2016  }}</ref>\n\nPatel was critical of the UK's decision to invest DFID funds to support the [[Palestinian territories]] through [[UN]] agencies and the [[Palestinian Authority]]. In October 2016 she ordered a review of the funding procedure, temporarily freezing approximately a third of Britain's aid to the Palestinians during the review. In December 2016, DFID announced significant changes concerning future funding for the Palestinian Authority. DFID stated that future aid would go \"solely to vital health and education services, in order to meet the immediate needs of the Palestinian people and maximise value for money.\" This move was widely supported by Jewish groups, including the [[Jewish Leadership Council]] and the [[Zionist Federation of Great Britain and Ireland|Zionist Federation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/uk-cracks-down-on-palestinian-aid-following-three-month-freeze/|title=UK cracks down on Palestinian aid following three-month freeze|last=Frazer|first=Jenni|date=16 December 2016|website=Jewish News Online|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109025819/http://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/uk-cracks-down-on-palestinian-aid-following-three-month-freeze/|archivedate=9 November 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=8 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-41853561|title=Priti Patel held undisclosed meetings in Israel|date=3 November 2017|publisher=BBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171105055901/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-41853561|archivedate=5 November 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=8 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Patel and the Labour MEP [[Neena Gill]] were the two UK winners of the [[Pravasi Bharatiya Samman]], the highest honour that the Indian government gives to [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|non-resident Indians or people of Indian origin]]. She was given the award for her public service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mea.gov.in/press-releases.htm?dtl/27911/Pravasi+Bharatiya+Samman+Awards2017|title=Pravasi Bharatiya Samman Awards-2017|publisher=[[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Ministry of External Affairs]]|date=9 January 2017|accessdate=15 September 2019}}</ref> In the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|June snap general election]], she was re-elected as MP for Witham with a majority 18,646 votes.<ref name=BBC2019/>\n\nIn March 2020, it was reported that while serving as International Development Secretary Patel was alleged to have \u201charassed and belittled\u201d staff in her private office in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Syal|first=Rajeev|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/mar/03/dominic-cummings-fostering-culture-of-bullying-says-labour|title=Priti Patel accused of bullying a third senior civil servant|date=2020-03-04|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-04|last2=Stewart|first2=Heather|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n====Meetings with Israeli officials and resignation====\nOn 3 November 2017, the [[BBC]]'s Diplomatic correspondent [[James Landale]] broke the news that Patel had held meetings in Israel in August 2017 without telling the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Office]]. She was accompanied by [[Stuart Polak, Baron Polak|Lord Polak]], honorary president of [[Conservative Friends of Israel]] (CFI). The meetings, up to a dozen in number, took place while Patel was on a \"private holiday\". Patel met [[Yair Lapid]], the leader of Israel's centrist [[Yesh Atid]] party, and reportedly made visits to several organisations where official departmental business was discussed. The BBC reported that \"According to one source, at least one of the meetings was held at the suggestion of the Israeli ambassador to London. In contrast, British diplomats in Israel were not informed about Ms Patel's plans.\"<ref name=\"bbc_jameslandel\">{{cite news|last=Landale|first=James|authorlink=James Landale|title=Priti Patel held undisclosed meetings in Israel|date=3 November 2017|publisher=[[BBC News]]|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-41853561|accessdate=7 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171105055901/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-41853561|archivedate=5 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIt was also reported that, following the meetings, Patel had recommended that the Department for International Development give international aid money to field hospitals run by the Israeli army in the [[Golan Heights]].  Although these hospitals have been described by the British Prime Minister's official spokesman as \"provid[ing] medical support for Syrian refugees\",<ref name=\"telearmy\">{{cite news |date= 7 November 2017 |title= Priti Patel suggested UK should 'give aid to Israeli army' after secret meeting with Benjamin Netanyahu |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/11/07/priti-patel-suggested-uk-should-give-aid-israeli-army-secret/ |work= [[The Daily Telegraph]] |access-date= 7 November 2017 |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20171107195759/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/11/07/priti-patel-suggested-uk-should-give-aid-israeli-army-secret/ |archivedate= 7 November 2017 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> Israeli officials have refused to identify who they treat in them, and whether they are regime forces, rebels or civilians.<ref name=interacting>{{Cite news |last= Lewis |first= Avi |date= 7 December 2014 |title= UN: Israel interacting with rebels on Syrian border |url= https://www.timesofisrael.com/un-israel-interacting-with-rebels-on-syrian-border/ |website= [[The Times of Israel]] |access-date= 10 November 2017 |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170619063953/http://www.timesofisrael.com/un-israel-interacting-with-rebels-on-syrian-border/ |archivedate= 19 June 2017 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> Western media reports suggest that Israel is aiding and funding Syrian opposition organisations in the [[Syrian civil war]].<ref>\"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/israel-giving-secret-aid-syrian-rebels-bashar-al-assad-golah-heights-hezbollah-fursan-al-joulan-a7797151.html Israel \u2018giving secret aid to Syrian rebels\u2019, report says] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827212558/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/israel-giving-secret-aid-syrian-rebels-bashar-al-assad-golah-heights-hezbollah-fursan-al-joulan-a7797151.html |date=27 August 2017 }}\" by Bethan McKernan, ''[[The Independent]]'', 19 June 2017</ref><ref>\"[https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-gives-secret-aid-to-syrian-rebels-1497813430 Israel Gives Secret Aid to Syrian Rebels] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628103834/https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-gives-secret-aid-to-syrian-rebels-1497813430 |date=28 June 2017 }}\" by Rory Jones, Noam Raydan, and Suha Ma'ayeh, ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', 18 June 2017</ref>\n\nOn 4 November 2017, in an interview with ''[[The Guardian]]'', Patel stated<blockquote>Boris [Johnson] knew about the visit. The point is that the Foreign Office did know about this, Boris knew about [the trip]. I went out there, I paid for it. And there is nothing else to this. It is quite extraordinary. It is for the Foreign Office to go away and explain themselves. The stuff that is out there is it, as far as I am concerned. I went on holiday and met with people and organisations. As far as I am concerned, the Foreign Office have known about this. It is not about who else I met; I have friends out there.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Syal|first1=Rajeev|last2=Sherwood|first2=Harriet|title=Priti Patel accuses Foreign Office of briefing against her over Israel meetings|date=3 November 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/nov/03/priti-patel-held-undisclosed-meetings-israel|accessdate=7 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171105071417/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/nov/03/priti-patel-held-undisclosed-meetings-israel|archivedate=5 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/statement-from-international-development-secretary-priti-patel|title=Statement from International Development Secretary Priti Patel \u2013 GOV.UK|publisher=gov.uk|accessdate=9 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109025857/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/statement-from-international-development-secretary-priti-patel|archivedate=9 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nPatel faced calls to resign, with numerous political figures calling her actions a breach of the [[Ministerial Code (United Kingdom)|ministerial code]], which states: \"Ministers must ensure that no conflict arises, or could reasonably be perceived to arise, between their public duties and their private interests, financial or otherwise\".<ref name=\"teletoast\" /> [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] MP [[Jon Trickett]] said, \"She met with the prime minister, and all sorts in Israel, with a lobbyist \u2013 I don't think it is good enough to apologise as I really think this is a serious breach of the ministerial code. The Prime Minister really should be sacking her, or at the very very minimum referring it to the Cabinet Office for investigation\".<ref name=\"teletoast\">{{Cite news |last= Swinford |first= Steven |date= 6 November 2017 |title= Priti Patel should be 'toast' after failing to declare meeting with Israeli Prime Minister, senior Tories say |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/11/06/priti-patel-should-toast-failing-declare-meeting-israeli-prime |work= [[The Daily Telegraph]] |access-date= 6 November 2017 |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20171106234803/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/11/06/priti-patel-should-toast-failing-declare-meeting-israeli-prime/ |archivedate= 6 November 2017 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 6 November, Patel was summoned to meet the Prime Minister [[Theresa May]], who then said that Patel had been \"reminded of her responsibilities\" and announced plans for the ministerial code of conduct to be tightened.<ref>{{cite news |title=PM plans new ministerial code after Priti Patel apology |date=7 November 2017 |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-41896756 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107194711/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-41896756 |archivedate=7 November 2017  }}</ref> Patel released an apology for her actions, and corrected her remarks to ''The Guardian'', which she said gave the false impression that the Foreign Secretary knew about the trip before it happened, and that the only meetings she had had were those then in the public domain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/statement-from-international-development-secretary-priti-patel|title=Statement from International Development Secretary Priti Patel|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref> According to Downing Street, May learned of the meetings when the BBC broke the story on 3 November.<ref>{{cite news|title=Priti Patel resigns from Cabinet over undisclosed meetings with Israeli officials|url=http://www.itv.com/news/2017-11-08/priti-patel/|accessdate=8 November 2017|publisher=ITV News|date=8 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108072812/http://www.itv.com/news/2017-11-08/priti-patel/|archivedate=8 November 2017}}</ref> When May hosted Netanyahu the previous day for the [[Balfour Declaration]] centenary, she was not aware that her minister had had meetings with him in August.\n\nIn the days after Patel's meeting with the Prime Minister and public apology, there were further revelations about her contacts with Israel, including details of two more undisclosed meetings with Israeli officials in Westminster and New York in September 2017,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-41923007|title=Priti Patel quits over Israel meetings row|date=8 November 2017|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> that Patel had not disclosed when she met the Prime Minister on 6th.<ref name=\"FT_2017_11_08\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/c7f278ac-c3c8-11e7-a1d2-6786f39ef675|title=Priti Patel returns to face uproar over Israel trip|last1=Mance|first1=Henry|last2=Pickard|first2=Jim|date=8 November 2017|work=[[Financial Times]]|language=en-GB|access-date=4 August 2019}}</ref> As a result of these further revelations Patel was summoned to Downing Street once more on 8 November, where she met with the Prime Minister and subsequently resigned from her cabinet position, after 16 months in the post.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-41923007|title=Priti Patel quits over Israel meetings row|date=8 November 2017|work=BBC News|accessdate=8 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108194221/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-41923007|archivedate=8 November 2017}}</ref> She was replaced by pro-[[Brexit]] MP [[Penny Mordaunt]] the following day.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/nov/09/penny-mordaunt-replaces-priti-patel-as-international-development-secretary|title=Penny Mordaunt replaces Priti Patel in May's cabinet|work=The Guardian|date=9 November 2017|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109150500/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/nov/09/penny-mordaunt-replaces-priti-patel-as-international-development-secretary|archivedate=9 November 2017}}</ref> Patel claimed that, following her resignation, she was \"overwhelmed with support from colleagues across the political divide\" and from her constituents.<ref>\"[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-essex-41954049 Priti Patel 'overwhelmed' by support after quitting cabinet] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171113084559/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-essex-41954049 |date=13 November 2017 }}\", ''BBC News'', 11 November 2017</ref><ref>\"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/priti-patel-speaks-sacked-international-development-secretary-a8050271.html Priti Patel says she has been 'overwhelmed with support' in first comments since being forced to resign] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171116225208/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/priti-patel-speaks-sacked-international-development-secretary-a8050271.html |date=16 November 2017 }}\" by Rachel Roberts, ''The Independent'', 12 November 2017</ref>\n\n=== Backbencher: 2017\u20132019 ===\n[[File:Rt Hon Priti Patel MP - Tortola, 24 September 2017 (23479788538).jpg|thumb|right|Patel visiting British troops in 2017]]\n\nIn May 2018, Patel questioned the impartiality of the [[Electoral Commission (United Kingdom)|Electoral Commission]] and called for it to investigate [[Britain Stronger in Europe]] or to end its inquiry into the [[Vote Leave]] campaign. Patel expressed concern that Britain Stronger in Europe had been provided with services by other remain campaigns without declaring the expenditure in the appropriate way.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/may/27/priti-patel-calls-investigation-remain-campaign-spending-brexit|title=Priti Patel calls for investigation into remain campaign spending|date=27 May 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In August 2018, the Electoral Commission reported that there was no evidence that Britain Stronger in Europe had breached any laws on campaign spending.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-remain-campaign-spending-priti-patel-electoral-commission-tory-mp-a8474961.html|title=Electoral Commission dismisses Tory MP Priti Patel's claims about Remain campaign spending|date=2 August 2018|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, during the UK's [[Brexit]] negotiations, a government report was leaked which indicated that food supplies and the economy in the [[Republic of Ireland]] could be adversely affected in the event of a no-deal Brexit. Following the report, Patel commented: \"This paper appears to show the government were well aware Ireland will face significant issues in a no-deal scenario. Why hasn't this point been pressed home during negotiations?\" Some sections of the media reported her comments as a suggestion that Britain should exploit Ireland's fear of damage to its economy and food shortages to advance its position with the EU. She was criticised for insensitivity by several other MPs in the light of Britain's part in Ireland's [[Great Famine (Ireland)|Great Famine]] in the 19th century, in which a million people died. Patel said her comments had been taken out of context.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-ireland-food-shortages-threat-risk-priti-patel-negotiate-better-deal-a8672326.html|title=Britain should use risk of food shortages in Ireland to get better Brexit deal, says Priti Patel|date=7 December 2018|work=The Independent|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"irish\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-46488479|title=Irish 'food shortage' comments condemned|date=7 December 2018|work=BBC News}}</ref> Irish EU Commissioner [[Phil Hogan]] said that a food blockade would result in Britain starving, not Ireland, since 43% of food consumed in the UK comes from Ireland.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/dec/07/government-aides-tell-may-they-plan-to-quit-over-her-brexit-deal-mike-wood|title=No 10 hits back as pro-Brexit aides threaten to quit over backstop|last1=Stewart|first1=Heather|date=7 December 2018|work=The Guardian|last2=Syal|first2=Rajeev}}</ref> Journalist [[Eilis O'Hanlon]] criticised the media's characterisation of Patel's comments as a \"manipulative, sinister media-manufactured campaign of character assassination\", further elaborating that the \"divide between fact and comment broke down entirely in response to Priti Patel's comments.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/opinion/comment/eilis-ohanlon-brits-want-to-starve-the-irish-is-the-definition-of-fake-news-37607873.html|title=Eilis O'Hanlon: 'Brits want to starve the Irish' is the definition of fake news'|last=O'Hanlon|first=Eilis|date=9 December 2018|newspaper=[[Irish Independent]]|accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, Patel tweeted supportive messages for [[Turning Point UK]].<ref name=\"guardian-walker\">{{cite news|first1=Peter|last1=Walker|accessdate=4 February 2019|title=Tory MPs back youth group with apparent links to US far right|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/feb/04/tory-mps-back-rightwing-youth-group-turning-point-uk|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=4 February 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\"independent-dearden\">{{cite news|accessdate=2 February 2019|title=Tory MPs voice support for new UK branch of 'sinister' right-wing US group|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/turning-point-uk-jacob-rees-mogg-conservative-right-wing-group-launch-tory-a8762351.html|date=4 February 2019|newspaper=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> In March 2019, Patel backed a pamphlet published by the [[TaxPayers' Alliance]] which called for the international development budget to be reformed, and for the UK alone to decide what constitutes aid, rather than international organisations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/18/priti-patel-joins-calls-for-radical-shake-up-of-aid-budget-rules|title=Priti Patel joins calls for radical shake-up of aid budget rules|last=Wintour|first=Patrick|date=18 March 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n===Home Secretary: 2019\u2013present===\n[[File:PM Johnson and HS Patel at Home Office.jpg|thumb|right|Patel as Home Secretary with Prime Minister Boris Johnson in 2019]]\nPatel was appointed Home Secretary by Boris Johnson in July 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/boris-johnson-goes-to-work-as-prime-minister-nh55w33c0|title=Boris Johnson goes to work as prime minister|first=Elliott|last=Francis|date=24 July 2019|via=thetimes.co.uk}}</ref> Shortly after her appointment, news had transpired that, in May 2019, Patel began working for [[Viasat, Inc.|Viasat]] as a strategic adviser on a salary of \u00a35,000 a month for five hours\u2019 work a month, without seeking prior approval from the government's [[Advisory Committee on Business Appointments]], leading to accusations that she has broken the ministerial code for a second time.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Grierson |first1=Jamie |title=Priti Patel accused of breaching ministerial code for second time |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/26/priti-patel-accused-of-breaching-ministerial-code-for-second-time |work=The Guardian |date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In the December general election, she was re-elected as MP for Witham with an increased majority of 24,082 (48.8%) votes.<ref name=BBC2019/>\n\nIn January 2020, a report by the Youth Empowerment and Innovation Project said that Patel's approach to tackling youth radicalisation was \"madness\" and the Home Office had been \"disengaged\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Townsend |first1=Mark |title=Priti Patel's plan to tackle radicalised youth is so flawed it's mad, says study |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/26/priti-patel-radicalised-youth-plan-so-flawed-its-mad |website=The Guardian |accessdate=26 January 2020 |date=26 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Patel launched a [[Points-based immigration system (United Kingdom)|points-based immigration system]], which will take effect from 1 January 2021.<ref>{{cite press release |url= https://www.gov.uk/government/news/hurricane-irma-foreign-secretarys-visit-to-the-uk-overseas-territories-in-the-Caribbean|title=UK announces new points-based immigration system (dead link)|date=19 February 2020|accessdate=20 February 2020|website=gov.uk}}</ref> The system will aim to reduce the number of immigrants to the UK by requiring visa applicants to meet a set of criteria, such as a salary threshold, ability to speak English, academic qualifications and working in an understaffed industry.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/nri/visa-and-immigration/priti-patel-launches-uks-historic-points-based-visa-system/articleshow/74210378.cms|title=UK Visa: Priti Patel launches UK's 'historic' points-based visa system|work=The Economic Times|date=20 February 2020|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThat same month she came under scrutiny for trying to \"force out\" [[Philip Rutnam|Sir Philip Rutnam]], the most senior civil servant in her department.<ref>{{cite web |title=Priti Patel 'tried to force out top civil servant' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51571619 |website=[[BBC]] |accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Murphy |first1=Joe |title=Priti Patel tried to get rid of top official Sir Philip Rutnam amid 'atmosphere of fear' |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/priti-patel-sir-philip-rutnam-home-office-row-a4367211.html |website=[[Evening Standard]] |accessdate=20 February 2020 |date=20 February 2020}}</ref> Rutnam resigned on 29 February, saying he would be suing the government for [[constructive dismissal]] and that he did not believe Patel's assertion that she had been uninvolved in an alleged campaign briefing against him.<ref>{{cite news |work=BBC News |title=Home Office boss quits over 'campaign against him' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51687287 |date=2020-02-29 |accessdate=2020-02-29}}</ref> Several days later, Patel sent an email to Home Office staff in which she expressed regret at Rutman's decision to resign and thanked him for his service.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-51727632|title=Patel's 'regret' over top adviser's resignation|date=2020-03-03|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-04|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, it was reported that Patel had turned down multiple invitations to appear in front of the [[Home Affairs Select Committee]] to discuss the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus outbreak]]. Patel refused four invitations, since January 2020, to appear before the Committee.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52224203|title=Patel turns down committee appearance four times|date=2020-04-08|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Political ideology and views==\n\nPatel is considered to be on the right-wing of the Conservative Party,<ref name=\"rightwing2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jul/15/priti-patel-tory-rightwinger-promoted-to-treasury|title=Tory rightwinger Priti Patel promoted to Treasury|last=Mason|first=Rowena|date=15 July 2014|work=The Guardian|access-date=10 November 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305001314/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jul/15/priti-patel-tory-rightwinger-promoted-to-treasury|archivedate=5 March 2016}}</ref> with the ''[[Total Politics]]'' website noting that some saw her as a \"modern-day [[Norman Tebbit]]\".<ref name=\"rightwing1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.totalpolitics.com/articles/interview/priti-patel-saviour-tory-right|title=Priti Patel: saviour of the Tory Right|date=5 October 2012|work=TotalPolitics.com|access-date=10 November 2017|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005160644/https://www.totalpolitics.com/articles/interview/priti-patel-saviour-tory-right|archivedate=5 October 2016}}</ref> In ''[[The Guardian]]'', the economics commentator Aditya Chakrabortty characterised her as \"an out-and-out right-winger\" who has no desire to \"claim the centre ground\" in politics.<ref>{{cite news |first=Aditya|last=Chakrabortty |date=23 August 2016 |title=A death foretold: watch as Priti Patel trashes our proud record on aid |website=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/aug/23/priti-patel-foreign-aid-world-poverty |accessdate=20 September 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920145236/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/aug/23/priti-patel-foreign-aid-world-poverty |archivedate=20 September 2016  }}</ref> Patel has cited Thatcher as her political hero,<ref name=totalpolitics/> and has described herself as a \"massive Thatcherite\" (\"I apologise to no one for that\"),<ref>{{Cite journal|journal=[[The House (magazine)|The House]]|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/conservative-party/house/95635/priti-patel-conservative-party-retreating|title=Priti Patel: The Conservative party is retreating from the battle of ideas|first=Sebastian|last=Whale|date=1 June 2018}}</ref> with various news sources characterising her as a [[Thatcherism|Thatcherite]],<ref name=totalpolitics>{{cite news|first=Tom|last=Gockelen-Kozlowski |title=Priti Patel: saviour of the Tory Right |website=Total Politics |date=5 October 2012 |url=https://www.totalpolitics.com/articles/interview/priti-patel-saviour-tory-right |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005160644/https://www.totalpolitics.com/articles/interview/priti-patel-saviour-tory-right |archivedate=5 October 2016  }}</ref><ref name=Warrell/><ref name=week>{{cite news |date=1 March 2016 |title=Priti Patel: the rising star tipped to lead Brexit campaign |work=The Week |url=http://www.theweek.co.uk/brexit/70134/priti-patel-the-rising-star-tipped-to-lead-brexit-campaign |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006165413/http://www.theweek.co.uk/brexit/70134/priti-patel-the-rising-star-tipped-to-lead-brexit-campaign |archivedate=6 October 2016  }}</ref> and while profiling Patel for ''[[The Independent]]'', Tom Peck wrote that she \"could scarcely be more of a Thatcherite\".<ref name=\"thatcherite1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/priti-patel-profile-tory-robot-poised-for-anti-eu-reboot-a6885531.html|title=Priti Patel: Tory 'robot' poised for anti-EU reboot|date=20 February 2016|work=The Independent|access-date=10 November 2017|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107223939/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/priti-patel-profile-tory-robot-poised-for-anti-eu-reboot-a6885531.html|archivedate=7 November 2017}}</ref> She has also previously served as a vice-chair of [[Conservative Friends of Israel]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.cfoi.co.uk/AboutCFI/ |title=About Conservative Friends of Israel |publisher=Conservative Friends of Israel |accessdate=22 September 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809004850/http://www2.cfoi.co.uk/AboutCFI/ |archivedate=9 August 2011  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/priti-patel-the-ambitious-politician-whose-reach-exceeded-her-grasp-1.447636|title=Priti Patel: the ambitious politician whose reach exceeded her grasp|last=Dysch|first=Marcus|date=8 November 2017|accessdate=24 July 2019|work=Jewish Chronicle}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Priti Patel MP.jpg|thumb|left|Patel speaking in 2012]]\n\nShe has taken robust stances on crime, garnering media attention after she argued for the restoration of capital punishment on the BBC's ''[[Question Time (TV series)|Question Time]]'' in September 2011,<ref>{{cite news|last=Helyer |first=Rachel |date=23 September 2011 |title=Furore as Priti Patel urges return of death penalty |url=http://www.theweek.co.uk/people-news/1961/furore-priti-patel-urges-return-death-penalty |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314060951/http://www.theweek.co.uk/people-news/1961/furore-priti-patel-urges-return-death-penalty|archivedate=14 March 2016 |work=The Week|accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Swinford |first=Steven |date=13 May 2015 |title=Priti Patel refuses to say whether she wants to bring back death penalty |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/crime/11601935/Priti-Patel-refuses-to-say-whether-she-wants-to-bring-back-death-penalty.html |archivedate=14 November 2017 |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=11 November 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171114201929/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/crime/11601935/Priti-Patel-refuses-to-say-whether-she-wants-to-bring-back-death-penalty.html  }}</ref> although in 2016 she stated that she no longer held this view.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/patel-backtracks-on-support-for-the-death-penalty-32hw2n76r|title=Patel backtracks on support for the death penalty|first=Michael|last=Savage|date=15 September 2016|work=The Times}}</ref> Patel [[Felony disenfranchisement|opposes prisoner voting]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-politics-12418281/prisoners-voters-john-prescott-and-priti-patel-on-european-law|title=Prisoners' voters: John Prescott and Priti Patel on European law|publisher=BBC News|date=10 February 2011|accessdate=24 September 2019}}</ref> She has also opposed allowing [[Jeremy Bamber]], who was convicted of murder in her constituency, access to media to protest his innocence.<ref>{{cite news|title=Why was killer Bamber given access to media?|date=13 September 2010|work=Maldon Standard|url=http://www.maldonandburnhamstandard.co.uk/news/8388603.Why_was_killer_Bamber_given_access_to_media_/|accessdate=25 February 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140719203944/http://www.maldonandburnhamstandard.co.uk/news/8388603.Why_was_killer_Bamber_given_access_to_media_/|archivedate=19 July 2014}}</ref> Patel voted against the [[Marriage (Same Sex Couples) Act 2013|2013 Marriage (Same Sex Couples) Bill]], which introduced same-sex marriage in England and Wales.<ref>{{cite web|title=MP-by-MP: Gay marriage vote|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-21346694|website=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nPatel has been criticised by some for raising issues in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] related to her time working for the tobacco and alcohol industries.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |last=Doward |first=Jamie |date=3 May 2014 |title=Tory cigarette packaging rebel Priti Patel is ex-tobacco lobbyist |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/may/03/tory-cigarette-packaging-rebel-tobacco-lobbyist |website=The Guardian |accessdate=31 May 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150315031159/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/may/03/tory-cigarette-packaging-rebel-tobacco-lobbyist |archivedate=15 March 2015  }}</ref> As a parliamentarian, Patel has been consistently supportive of tobacco industry viewpoints: in October 2010, she voted for the smoking ban to be overturned; in December 2010, she signed a letter requesting that plain packaging for cigarettes be reconsidered. Patel has also campaigned with the drinks industry, holding a reception in parliament for the ''Call Time On Duty Campaign'' in favour of ending the alcohol duty escalator supported by the Wine and Spirit Trade Association, the Scotch Whisky Association and the [[TaxPayers' Alliance]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wsta.co.uk/press/697-call-time-on-duty-campaign-makes-its-case-to-parliamentarians |title=Call Time on Duty campaign makes its case to Parliamentarians |publisher=Wsta.co.uk |accessdate=30 May 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530054552/http://wsta.co.uk/press/697-call-time-on-duty-campaign-makes-its-case-to-parliamentarians |archivedate=30 May 2015  }}</ref>\n\nSpeaking on [[BBC Radio Kent]] in March 2018, Patel said that she found the commonly-used abbreviation ''BME'' (for [[Classification of ethnicity in the United Kingdom|Black and Minority Ethnic]]) to be \"patronising and insulting\". This was because being born in Britain, she considered herself British first and foremost.<ref name=BME/>\n\n==Personal life==\nPatel has been married to Alex Sawyer since 2004.<ref>{{cite book|first=Lucy|last=Hume|title=People of Today 2017|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oAM7DwAAQBAJ&pg=RA1-PA1817|date=5 October 2017|publisher=Debrett's|isbn=978-1-9997670-3-7|page=1817|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180204164306/https://books.google.com/books?id=oAM7DwAAQBAJ&pg=RA1-PA1817|archivedate=4 February 2018}}</ref> Sawyer is a [[marketing consultant]] for the stock exchange [[NASDAQ]]. He is also a Conservative [[councillor]] and Cabinet Member for Communities on the council of the [[London Borough of Bexley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://democracy.bexley.gov.uk/mgUserInfo.aspx?UID=177|title=Councillor Alex Sawyer|accessdate=24 September 2019|publisher=Bexley Borough Council}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://directory.londoncouncils.gov.uk/directory/bexley/executive/|title=London Borough of Bexley|publisher=London Councils|accessdate=9 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110225244/http://directory.londoncouncils.gov.uk/directory/bexley/executive/|archivedate=10 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=Kenber/> Sawyer also worked part-time as her office manager from February 2014 to August 2017.<ref name=Kenber>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/priti-patels-husband-comes-off-the-payroll-brhr75j95|title=Priti Patel's husband comes off the payroll|work=The Times|date=8 August 2017|last=Kenber|first=Billy}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/11706561/One-in-four-MPs-employs-a-family-member-the-full-list-revealed.html|title=One in five MPs employs a family member: the full list revealed|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=29 June 2015|last=Hope|first=Christopher|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170402065627/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/11706561/One-in-four-MPs-employs-a-family-member-the-full-list-revealed.html|archivedate=2 April 2017}}</ref> Together they have a son born in August 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisistotalessex.co.uk/news/Newborn-Freddie-Tory-party-s-youngest-member/article-268112-detail/article.html |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130505130100/http://www.thisistotalessex.co.uk/news/Newborn-Freddie-Tory-party-s-youngest-member/article-268112-detail/article.html |url-status=dead |archivedate=5 May 2013 |title=Newborn Freddie is the Tory party's youngest member |work=This is Total Essex |date=14 August 2008 |accessdate=22 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Priti Patel}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.priti4witham.com/}}\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = priti-patel/4066 | hansard = | hansardcurr = <!-- 5618 --> | guardian = 9319/priti-patel | publicwhip = Priti_Patel | theywork = priti_patel | bbc = 37703.stm | journalisted = }}\n*{{C-SPAN}}\n* [http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b09drhhk 2017 Profile of Patel] on [[BBC Radio Four]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br />for [[Witham (UK Parliament constituency)|Witham]]|years=[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Gauke]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Exchequer Secretary to the Treasury]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Damian Hinds]]|rows=2}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Esther McVey]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department for Work and Pensions|Minister of State for Employment]]|years=2015\u20132016}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Justine Greening]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for International Development]]|years=2016\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Penny Mordaunt]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sajid Javid]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Home Secretary]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Great Offices of State}}\n{{Cabinet of David Cameron}}\n{{Second Cameron Cabinet}}\n{{First May Cabinet}}\n{{Second May Cabinet}}\n{{Johnson Cabinet}}\n{{Home Secretaries}}\n{{G8-Interior}}\n{{Secretary of State for International Development}}\n{{East of England Conservative Party MPs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patel, Priti}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Keele University]]\n[[Category:English people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Essex]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Critics of the European Union]]\n[[Category:British politicians of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Gujarati descent]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Cabinet of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Watford Grammar School for Girls]]\n[[Category:People from Harrow, London]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of State for the Home Department]]\n[[Category:Recipients of Pravasi Bharatiya Samman]]\n[[Category:Female interior ministers]]\n[[Category:Female critics of feminism]]\n", "name_user": "DRMorgans", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Priti_Patel"}
{"title_page": "Goran Krivokapi\u0107", "text_new": "'''Goran Krivokapi\u0107''' (\u0413\u043e\u0440\u0430\u043d \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u043a\u0430\u043f\u0438\u045b), born 7 May 1979, is an award-winning Montenegrin [[classical guitarist]].\n[[Image:Gik05.jpg|175px|thumb|right|Goran in concert]]\n\n==Early years and education==\nDue to the [[1979 Montenegro earthquake]], Krivokapi\u0107 was born in [[Belgrade]], [[SR Serbia]], [[SFR Yugoslavia]]. He started his music education at the age of eight with Mi\u0107o Poznanovi\u0107 at the Music School of [[Herceg Novi]] in [[Montenegro]]. When he was nine he began to perform publicly, and soon built a reputation which led to the famous montenegrin poet and television personality Dragan Radulovi\u0107 to produce a documentary about him in 1993. In 1996 he furthered his studies at the [[Faculty of Music in Belgrade]] in the class of Srdjan To\u0161i\u0107, graduating in 2000. From 2000 he continued with [[Hubert K\u00e4ppel]] and Roberto Aussel at the [[Hochschule f\u00fcr Musik K\u00f6ln]] in Germany, where he graduated and received the artistic performance (K\u00fcnstlerische Ausbildung) and postgraduate (\"Konzertexamen\") degrees. He then completed a master's degree at the [[Conservatorium Maastricht]] in the Netherlands with [[Carlo Marchione]] and a Masters after Masters with Raphaella Smits at [[LUCA School of Arts]], Campus Lemmeninstituut, in Leuven, Belgium. \n\n==Awards and prizes==\nKrivokapi\u0107 won his first international competition, \"Petar Konjovic\" in Belgrade at the age of fourteen. In order to finance his studies and living costs in Germany he  continued participating in competitions, winning a total of 19 international first prizes.\n\n\u2022 1994 - Petar Jonkovic, Belgrade \n\n\u2022 1995 - [http://www.concorsostresa.it/documents/StresaRulesAdmission2019.pdf Citta di Stresa Music Competition](Guitar category)\n\n\u2022 1996 - Petar Jonkovic, Belgrade \n\n\u2022 1997 - Corfu International Guitar Competition Greece.\n\n\u2022 2000 - XVI International Guitar Competition [[Andr\u00e9s Segovia]] in Almu\u00f1ecar, Spain. \n\n\u2022 2000 - XXXIII [[Michele Pittaluga International Classical Guitar Competition]] (member of the [[World Federation of International Music Competitions]] in Alessandria, Italy.                             \n\n\u2022 2001 - XXIII [http://guitareconcoursbartoli.chez.com/ International Guitar Competition Rene Bartoli] in Aix-en-Provence, France. First prize and audience prize.\n\n\u2022 2001 - Wesel Guitar Festival and Competition, Germany.        \n\n\u2022 2003 - XXXII International Guitar Competition Fernando Sor in Rome, Italy.                       \n\n\u2022 2003 - I Koblenz International Guitar Competition, Koblenz, Germany.  \n\n\u2022 2003 - Velez Malaga International Guitar Competition, Spain.\n\n\u2022 2004 - International Guitar Festival and Competition Arhontiko, Arhanes, Crete.                                     \n\n\u2022 2004 - I Iserlohn International Guitar Competition, Iserlohn, Germany.   \n\n\u2022 2004 - [[Ruggero Chiesa]] Citta di Camogli, Italy.                              \n\n\u2022 2004 - VII [[Alhambra International Guitar Competition]] in Alcoy, Spain.                                     \n\n\u2022 2004 - XXV International Guitar Competition Mauro Giuliani in Bari, Italy.                             \n\n\u2022 2004 - XXII [http://www.guitarfoundation.org/ Guitar Foundation of America International Solo Competition] in Montr\u00e9al, Canada.                                   \n\n\u2022 2004 -  XXXI [https://www.culturaviva.cl/concurso-internacional-de-ejecucion-musical-luis-sigall/ Dr. Luis Sigall International Competition for Musical Performance] (member of WFIMC) in Vi\u00f1a del Mar, Chile.                 \n\n\u2022 2007 - Heinsberg International Guitar Competition, Germany.\n\nTwo Chittara D\u2019oro (Golden Guitar) awards followed at the Alessandria International Guitar Convention which is held each year in Italy: 2005 for Best Young Guitarist Of The Year, and 2006 for his debut CD. \n\n==Artistic life==\nGoran Krivokapi\u0107 hen he has performed extensively all over Europe, North and South America, Asia, Africa and Russia, in halls such as Concertgebouw in Amsterdam, Tchaikovsky Hall in Moscow, Lubkowitz Palace in Vienna, Auditorio Conde Duque in Madrid and Saint Petersburg Philharmonia. \n\nAs a soloist, Goran Krivokapi\u0107 has performed with the Slovak Chamber Orchestra of Bohdan Warchal, Belgrade Philharmonic Orchestra, Chilean Symphony Orchestra, Moscow Symphony Orchestra, Turin Philharmonic, Folkwang Chamber Orchestra, Istanbul State Symphony Orchestra, New Russian Symphony Orchestra, St. George String Orchestra, Harmonie Universelle, Berliner Camerata, Montenegrin Symphony Orchestra, Romanian National Radio Orchestra, Philharmonic Orchestra Bremerhaven, Johannesburg Symphony Orchestra, Kwazulu-Natal Philharmonic and Shenyang Symphony Orchestra amongst others.   \n\nAs a performer, teacher and adjudicator Krivokapi\u0107 attended international festivals such as Festspiele Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, musicAmuseo, Festival Internacional de M\u00fasica y Danza de Granada, Kotor Art, Koblenz International Guitar Festival, Mittelrhein Musik Festival, Central-European Music Festival, Forum Gitarre Wien, Iserlohn International Guitar Festival, GFA International Guitar Convention, International Guitar Festival Aarhus, Aalborg International Guitar Festival, A Tempo Festival, Guitar Art Festival, Guitarras del Mundo, Festival Internacional de Violao Belo Horizonte, Festival Internacional de Guitarra Monterrey, Semanas Musicalas de Frutillar, Shenyang Guitar Festival, Changsha International Guitar Festival, Qinling International Guitar Festival and Daejon Guitar Festival. He has given masterclasses, lectures on Bach and workshops at Grieg Academy (Norway), State University of New York, University of Toronto, Hochschule f\u00fcr Musik Detmold, Indiana University Jacobs School of Music, Gnessin Russian Academy of Music (Moscow), Florida State University, Conservatorium Maastricht, University of Cape Town, University of Texas Dallas, Victoria Conservatory of Music, Chapman University, Royal Conservatory of Music in Montreal, Seoul National University, Arkansas State University, University of Manitoba, University of Texas in Brownsville, State Conservatory M.I. Glinka Nizhny Novgorod, University of Wisconsin, Loyola Marymount in Los Angeles, University of Veracruz and Tianjin Conservatory. He has been active in the \u201cRhapsody in School\u201d project on a regular basis, an outreach initiative founded by [[Lars Vogt]], which devotes itself to bringing classical music into the classroom. \n\nRegular features, broadcasts for television and radio include WDR, BBC, Hessischer Rundfunk, Bayerischer Rundfunk, SWR2, MDR,  Radio Bremen, Fox 7, WGBH Boston, Fine Music Radio, Classic FM, ABC Classic, RTCG, TV Arte, TV Politika and TV Montenegro. His recordings and performances have been highly praised and featured in Gramophone Magazine (UK), Classical Guitar Magazine (UK), Akustik Gitarre (Germany), Gendai Guitar Magazine (Japan), The WholeNote (Canada), Soundboard Magazine (USA) Neue Musikzeitung (Germany), Les Cahiers de la Guitare (France), Musica (Italy), Seicorde (Italy) and MobilArt (Montenegro).  \n\nIn 2017 Goran Krivokapi\u0107 was featured giving a masterclass on Joaquin Rodrigo\u2019s Concierto de Aranjuez for DakApp and [[Medici.tv|Medici.TV]].    \n\nIn 2005 Krivokapi\u0107 and classical guitarist  [[Danijel Cerovi\u0107]] formed the [[Montenegrin Guitar Duo]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://montenegringuitarduo.com/|title=Archived copy|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306110751/http://montenegringuitarduo.com/|archive-date=2019-03-06|access-date=2019-03-09}}</ref>In 2013 their debut CD was published by the Montenegrin Music Centre. The recording features works by Domeniconi, Piazzolla and Bogdanovi\u0107. [[Naxos Records]] released two volumes of J.S.Bach\u2019s English Suites, transcribed by the duo for two guitars in 2015 (Suites 1-3) and 2018 (Suites 4-6). \n\nGoran Krivokapi\u0107\u2019s musical focus lies on the development of new works for classical guitar, mainly through making his own transcriptions of baroque and classical works, and collaborating with contemporary composers. [https://productionsdoz.com/nos-artistes/drozd-gerard?lg=en_US Gerard Drozd] dedicated his [https://www.thisisclassicalguitar.com/tag/gerard-drozd/ Concierto de Gliwice Opus 175], which Krivokapi\u0107 premiered with the AUKSO Chamber Orchestra in 2018, conducted by [https://pl.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marek_Mo\u015b Marek Mo\u015b]. Drozd\u2019s Concierto for two guitars and string quartett Opus 140, dedicated to the Montenegrin Guitar Duo was premiered by Krivokapi\u0107 and Cerovi\u0107, together with the Camerata Quartett in 2013, as well as his Suite for two guitars Opus 150, dedicated to the Montenegrin Guitar Duo and premiered by them in 2014. In 2011 Drozd wrote a piece \u201cFavola per Luka\u201d to commemorate the birth of Krivokapic\u2019s son. The premiere recording of [[Hendrik Hofmeyr]]\u2019s [https://open.spotify.com/track/2baRlppIh7ETO7NQgRaeVC?nd=1 Rapsodia Notturna per chitarra e pianoforte], written for Krivokapi\u0107 and Corneli Smit, and [https://music.apple.com/de/album/chamber-music-for-guitar-and-piano/844269331?l=en Sonate Printani\u00e8re] by [[Du\u0161an Bogdanovi\u0107]] for guitar and piano was released in 2013 together with other original chamber music works for guitar and piano by KSGEXAUDIO. He premiered Hofmeyr\u2019s Lachrymae for guitar, which was written for him, during the Meesters op de Gitaar series at the Concertgebouw in Amsterdam in 2009. Hofmeyr wrote [https://openmusiclibrary.org/score/ad02b210-8777-4c4b-a7d8-15ba7bb7952b/ Diablerie] for viola and guitar for Krivokapi\u0107 and [https://de.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gareth_Lubbe Gareth Lubbe], which they premiered in 2019 at Krivokapi\u0107\u2019s inaugural concert at the Cologne University of Music (Wuppertal). [https://fr.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atanas_Ourkouzounov Atanas Ourkouzounov] dedicated his Chaconne for solo guitar to him. Other premiered works (performance and recordings) include his transcription of C.P.E. Bach\u2019s Sonata for flute Wq. 132 and piano sonata XVI:33 by Joseph Haydn, transcribed by Carlo Marchione. \n\nCurrently he is teaching guitar at [[LUCA School of Arts]], Campus Lemmeninstituut in Leuven, Belgium, the [[Prince Claus Conservatoire]] -Hanze University of Applied Sciences in Groningen, The Netherlands, University of Music Detmold, and is professor of guitar at the [[Cologne University of Music]], Germany.\n\n==Selected recordings==\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:KrivokapicCD.jpg|100px|thumb|top|Signed CD Cover]] -->\n\n\n'''\u2022 Guitar Recital'''  Naxos\n\n[http://www.naxos.com/catalogue/item.asp?item_code=8.557809 http://www.naxos.com/catalogue/item.asp?item_code=8.557809]\n\nRecorded at the St John Chrysostom Church, Newmarket, Ontario, Canada, 28 April \u2013 1 May 2005\nNAXOS 8.557809 [61:11]\n\n'''\u2022 Sor Guitar Music Opus 6-9'''  Naxos \n\nhttps://www.naxos.com/catalogue/item.asp?item_code=8.570502\n\n'''\u2022 J.S. Bach - English Suites 1-3''' Naxos\n\nhttps://www.naxos.com/catalogue/item.asp?item_code=8.573473\n\n'''\u2022 J.S. Bach - English Suites 4-6'''  Naxos\n\nhttps://www.naxos.com/catalogue/item.asp?item_code=8.573676\n\n'''\u2022''' '''Spanish Guitar Masterpieces'''  Naxos\n\nhttps://www.naxos.com/catalogue/item.asp?item_code=8.578343\n\n'''\u2022 Chamber Music for Guitar and Piano'''        KSGEXAUDIO\n\nhttps://music.apple.com/de/album/chamber-music-for-guitar-and-piano/844269331?l=en\n\nhttp://www.ksg-publishing.com/Produkte/67027.html\n\n'''\u2022 Sonate'''  Montenegrin Music Centre\n\nhttps://goran-krivokapic.com/discography-3/<br />\n\n'''\u2022 Montenegrin Guitar Duo'''  Montenegrin   Music C